Note:
This file handles whole-program analysis for link-time optimization.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Process whole-program call graph construction and analysis
- Handle global visibility analysis and unused code detection
- Manage whole-program type analysis and devirtualization opportunities
- Process inter-procedural analysis across entire program

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Whole-program analysis enables global optimization decisions
- Proper WPA provides complete program visibility for aggressive optimization
- WPA is foundation for maximum LTO effectiveness

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Complete program call graph construction
- Global reachability analysis from entry points
- Whole-program type hierarchy analysis
- Inter-procedural data flow analysis across entire program
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/analysis/call_graph.runa" as CallGraph
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIRProgram
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIRFunction
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIRNode
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIRTypeInfo
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dictionary
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/set.runa" as Set
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "runtime/io/filesystem/file_operations.runa" as FileOps
Import "runtime/integration/system_interface/wrappers/environment_manager.runa" as Env

@Reasoning
Whole-program analysis (WPA) is the foundation of link-time optimization.
It provides complete visibility into the entire program's structure, enabling
aggressive optimizations that are impossible with per-module compilation.

Key WPA Components:
1. Call Graph - Complete program call graph with cross-module edges
2. Type Hierarchy - Complete type system with all implementations
3. Reachability - Which functions/globals are actually used
4. Escape Analysis - Which values escape their allocation context
5. Side Effects - Which functions have observable effects
6. Devirtualization - Which virtual calls have unique implementations

WPA enables:
- Cross-module inlining based on complete call graph
- Dead code elimination at whole-program level
- Constant propagation across module boundaries
- Devirtualization when implementations are unique
- Function specialization based on actual usage patterns
- Global optimization decisions with complete information
@End Reasoning

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Type Definitions
Note: ============================================================================

@Implementation
WholeProgramAnalysis is the main structure containing all WPA results.

Fields:
- mir: Pointer to complete MIR program
- call_graph: Complete program call graph with all edges
- entry_functions: List of entry point function IDs (main, exported)
- reachable_functions: Set of function IDs reachable from entry points
- unreachable_functions: Set of dead function IDs
- type_hierarchy: Dictionary mapping type_id -> TypeHierarchyNode
- type_count: Number of types in hierarchy
- escape_info: Dictionary mapping value_id -> escape status (0=no escape, 1=escapes)
- side_effect_info: Dictionary mapping function_id -> side effect flags
- pure_functions: Set of function IDs that are pure (no side effects)
- const_functions: Set of function IDs that are const (no global state mutation)
- exported_functions: Set of function IDs that are exported
- address_taken_functions: Set of function IDs whose address is taken
- devirtualization_candidates: List of canonical 40-byte DevirtCandidate structs
- inlining_candidates: List of cross-module inlining opportunities
- constant_globals: Set of global variable IDs that are compile-time constants
- dce_plan: Pointer to DCEPlan struct (NEW, populated by identify_whole_program_dce)
- optimization_priorities: Dictionary mapping bucket-tagged optimization_id -> priority score (NEW)
- points_to_map: Lazily-allocated Dictionary cache used by get_points_to_set
  for memoising flow-insensitive points-to queries. Originally lived at
  offset 128, relocated to offset 144 in v0.0.8.5 P1-E v2 after the WPA
  struct grew to host the new dce_plan field at the previous slot. Moving
  the cache here (rather than threading it through every call chain)
  preserves the cache hit rate without colliding with the DCE plan
  pointer at offset 128.
- constant_prop_candidates: List of 24-byte CPCandidate structs (NEW, CP track)
- specialization_candidates: List of 32-byte SpecCandidate structs (NEW, CP track)

Memory layout (168 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0: mir (8 bytes)
Offset 8: call_graph (8 bytes)
Offset 16: entry_functions (8 bytes)
Offset 24: reachable_functions (8 bytes)
Offset 32: unreachable_functions (8 bytes)
Offset 40: type_hierarchy (8 bytes)
Offset 48: type_count (8 bytes)
Offset 56: escape_info (8 bytes)
Offset 64: side_effect_info (8 bytes)
Offset 72: pure_functions (8 bytes)
Offset 80: const_functions (8 bytes)
Offset 88: exported_functions (8 bytes)
Offset 96: address_taken_functions (8 bytes)
Offset 104: devirtualization_candidates (8 bytes)
Offset 112: inlining_candidates (8 bytes)
Offset 120: constant_globals (8 bytes)
Offset 128: dce_plan (8 bytes)
Offset 136: optimization_priorities (8 bytes)
Offset 144: points_to_map (8 bytes, lazily-allocated Dictionary cache for get_points_to_set)
Offset 152: constant_prop_candidates (8 bytes)
Offset 160: specialization_candidates (8 bytes)
@End Implementation

Type called "WholeProgramAnalysis":
    mir as Integer
    call_graph as Integer
    entry_functions as Integer
    reachable_functions as Integer
    unreachable_functions as Integer
    type_hierarchy as Integer
    type_count as Integer
    escape_info as Integer
    side_effect_info as Integer
    pure_functions as Integer
    const_functions as Integer
    exported_functions as Integer
    address_taken_functions as Integer
    devirtualization_candidates as Integer
    inlining_candidates as Integer
    constant_globals as Integer
    dce_plan as Integer
    optimization_priorities as Integer
    points_to_map as Integer
    constant_prop_candidates as Integer
    specialization_candidates as Integer
End Type

@Implementation
DCEPlan aggregates dead-code findings into a single descriptor consumed
by the CMO sweep passes.

Memory layout (40 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0:  dead_funcs        (8 bytes, List of function IDs sorted ascending)
Offset 8:  dead_func_count   (8 bytes)
Offset 16: dead_globals      (8 bytes, List of global IDs)
Offset 24: dead_global_count (8 bytes)
Offset 32: dead_types        (8 bytes, List of type IDs)
@End Implementation

Type called "DCEPlan":
    dead_funcs as Integer
    dead_func_count as Integer
    dead_globals as Integer
    dead_global_count as Integer
    dead_types as Integer
End Type

@Implementation
DevirtCandidate is the canonical 40-byte virtual-call devirtualization
candidate record produced by compute_devirtualization_candidates and
filtered/elevated by identify_virtual_call_elimination.

Memory layout (40 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0:  call_site       (8 bytes, MIR instruction pointer)
Offset 8:  target_func     (8 bytes, target function ID)
Offset 16: confidence      (8 bytes, 1=exact, 0=speculative)
Offset 24: verified        (8 bytes, 0=not yet verified, 1=verified)
Offset 32: is_speculative  (8 bytes, mirror of confidence==0 for O(1) bucket dispatch)
@End Implementation

Type called "DevirtCandidate":
    call_site as Integer
    target_func as Integer
    confidence as Integer
    verified as Integer
    is_speculative as Integer
End Type

@Implementation
CPCandidate records a constant-global propagation opportunity. The
use_count and value_size_est fields drive the bucket-0x0007 score in
compute_optimization_priorities.

Memory layout (24 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0:  global_id      (8 bytes)
Offset 8:  use_count      (8 bytes, LOAD count across reachable functions)
Offset 16: value_size_est (8 bytes, estimated MIR bytes saved by inlining)
@End Implementation

Type called "CPCandidate":
    global_id as Integer
    use_count as Integer
    value_size_est as Integer
End Type

@Implementation
SpecCandidate records a function-specialization opportunity. The
benefit and caller_count fields drive the bucket-0x0008 score in
compute_optimization_priorities. dominant_const_arg is the parameter
index whose actual argument is most often a constant across call
sites (-1 if no dominant constant arg detected).

Memory layout (32 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0:  function_id        (8 bytes)
Offset 8:  caller_count       (8 bytes)
Offset 16: benefit            (8 bytes, raw score from compute_specialization_benefit)
Offset 24: dominant_const_arg (8 bytes, parameter index with most constant args; -1 if none)
@End Implementation

Type called "SpecCandidate":
    function_id as Integer
    caller_count as Integer
    benefit as Integer
    dominant_const_arg as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: P1-E v3 scoring constants
Note: ============================================================================

@Implementation
Priority-score weight ratio 10:1:5 (cycle:size:enabling). The
calibration tracks LLVM LTO's ranker constants for x86_64-class
targets; cycle savings dominate, size penalty is mild, and enabling
score adds a moderate bonus for optimizations that unlock downstream
work. CALL_OVERHEAD_CYCLES=10 reflects the median observed cost of a
predicted direct call on modern x86_64; INDIRECT_CALL_OVERHEAD=20
adds the branch-target-buffer miss penalty for an unpredicted
indirect dispatch. MIR_BYTES_PER_INST_EST=8 reflects the average
post-codegen byte count for a typical MIR instruction in the v0.0.8.5
backend. SPECIALIZATION_BENEFIT_FLOOR=50 is the inflection point
below which specialization clones cost more than they save.
@End Implementation

Constant CYCLE_WEIGHT                  as Integer is 10
Constant SIZE_PENALTY_WEIGHT           as Integer is 1
Constant ENABLING_WEIGHT               as Integer is 5
Constant CALL_OVERHEAD_CYCLES          as Integer is 10
Constant INDIRECT_CALL_OVERHEAD        as Integer is 20
Constant MIR_BYTES_PER_INST_EST        as Integer is 8
Constant SPECIALIZATION_BENEFIT_FLOOR  as Integer is 50

Note: Bucket tags occupy the high 16 bits of the priority-Dict key;
Note: the low 48 bits hold the candidate index within the bucket.
Constant BUCKET_TAG_INLINING           as Integer is 1
Constant BUCKET_TAG_DEVIRT_EXACT       as Integer is 2
Constant BUCKET_TAG_DEVIRT_SPEC        as Integer is 3
Constant BUCKET_TAG_DCE_FUNC           as Integer is 4
Constant BUCKET_TAG_DCE_GLOBAL         as Integer is 5
Constant BUCKET_TAG_DCE_TYPE           as Integer is 6
Constant BUCKET_TAG_CP                 as Integer is 7
Constant BUCKET_TAG_SPEC               as Integer is 8

Note: Struct sizes used by allocators throughout the file.
Constant DEVIRT_CANDIDATE_SIZE         as Integer is 40
Constant DCE_PLAN_SIZE                 as Integer is 40
Constant CP_CANDIDATE_SIZE             as Integer is 24
Constant SPEC_CANDIDATE_SIZE           as Integer is 32
Constant WPA_STRUCT_SIZE               as Integer is 168

Note: MIR opcodes referenced by WPA passes.
Constant MIR_OP_LOAD                   as Integer is 20200
Constant MIR_OP_STORE                  as Integer is 20201
Constant MIR_OP_CALL                   as Integer is 20304
Constant MIR_OP_CALL_INDIRECT          as Integer is 20305

Note: Bucket-key bit-shift constant. 1 shifted left 48 bits = 2^48 used as
Note: a multiplier for composing bucket-tagged Dict keys.
Constant BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT         as Integer is 281474976710656

@Implementation
TypeHierarchyNode represents a type in the whole-program type hierarchy.

Fields:
- type_id: Unique type identifier
- type_info: Pointer to HIRTypeInfo
- parent_types: List of parent type IDs (interfaces, base classes)
- parent_count: Number of parent types
- child_types: List of child type IDs (implementations, derived classes)
- child_count: Number of child types
- virtual_methods: Dictionary mapping method_name -> MethodInfo
- method_count: Number of virtual methods
- is_sealed: Boolean (1 if type cannot be extended, 0 otherwise)
- is_abstract: Boolean (1 if type is abstract/interface, 0 otherwise)
- all_implementations: Set of all concrete type IDs implementing this type

Memory layout (88 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0: type_id (8 bytes)
Offset 8: type_info (8 bytes)
Offset 16: parent_types (8 bytes)
Offset 24: parent_count (8 bytes)
Offset 32: child_types (8 bytes)
Offset 40: child_count (8 bytes)
Offset 48: virtual_methods (8 bytes)
Offset 56: method_count (8 bytes)
Offset 64: is_sealed (8 bytes)
Offset 72: is_abstract (8 bytes)
Offset 80: all_implementations (8 bytes)
@End Implementation

Type called "TypeHierarchyNode":
    type_id as Integer
    type_info as Integer
    parent_types as Integer
    parent_count as Integer
    child_types as Integer
    child_count as Integer
    virtual_methods as Integer
    method_count as Integer
    is_sealed as Integer
    is_abstract as Integer
    all_implementations as Integer
End Type

@Implementation
MethodInfo represents a method in the type hierarchy.

Fields:
- method_name: Pointer to method name string
- method_signature: Pointer to method signature type
- declaring_type: Type ID where method is declared
- implementations: List of function IDs implementing this method
- implementation_count: Number of implementations
- is_final: Boolean (1 if method cannot be overridden, 0 otherwise)
- is_abstract: Boolean (1 if method is abstract, 0 otherwise)
- unique_implementation: Function ID if only one implementation exists (0 otherwise)

Memory layout (64 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0: method_name (8 bytes)
Offset 8: method_signature (8 bytes)
Offset 16: declaring_type (8 bytes)
Offset 24: implementations (8 bytes)
Offset 32: implementation_count (8 bytes)
Offset 40: is_final (8 bytes)
Offset 48: is_abstract (8 bytes)
Offset 56: unique_implementation (8 bytes)
@End Implementation

Type called "MethodInfo":
    method_name as Integer
    method_signature as Integer
    declaring_type as Integer
    implementations as Integer
    implementation_count as Integer
    is_final as Integer
    is_abstract as Integer
    unique_implementation as Integer
End Type

@Implementation
InterProceduralInfo contains inter-procedural analysis results for a function.

Fields:
- function_id: Function being analyzed
- escaping_parameters: Set of parameter indices that escape
- escaping_returns: Boolean (1 if return value escapes, 0 otherwise)
- memory_reads: Set of global variable IDs read by this function
- memory_writes: Set of global variable IDs written by this function
- indirect_reads: Boolean (1 if reads through pointers, 0 otherwise)
- indirect_writes: Boolean (1 if writes through pointers, 0 otherwise)
- calls_external: Boolean (1 if calls external functions, 0 otherwise)
- throws_exceptions: Boolean (1 if may throw exceptions, 0 otherwise)
- is_pure: Boolean (1 if pure function, 0 otherwise)
- is_const: Boolean (1 if const function, 0 otherwise)
- side_effect_flags: Bitfield of side effect categories

Memory layout (96 bytes, Tier 3 OWNED HEAP):
Offset 0: function_id (8 bytes)
Offset 8: escaping_parameters (8 bytes)
Offset 16: escaping_returns (8 bytes)
Offset 24: memory_reads (8 bytes)
Offset 32: memory_writes (8 bytes)
Offset 40: indirect_reads (8 bytes)
Offset 48: indirect_writes (8 bytes)
Offset 56: calls_external (8 bytes)
Offset 64: throws_exceptions (8 bytes)
Offset 72: is_pure (8 bytes)
Offset 80: is_const (8 bytes)
Offset 88: side_effect_flags (8 bytes)
@End Implementation

Type called "InterProceduralInfo":
    function_id as Integer
    escaping_parameters as Integer
    escaping_returns as Integer
    memory_reads as Integer
    memory_writes as Integer
    indirect_reads as Integer
    indirect_writes as Integer
    calls_external as Integer
    throws_exceptions as Integer
    is_pure as Integer
    is_const as Integer
    side_effect_flags as Integer
End Type

Note: Side effect flag constants
Constant SIDE_EFFECT_NONE as Integer is 0
Constant SIDE_EFFECT_MEMORY_READ as Integer is 1
Constant SIDE_EFFECT_MEMORY_WRITE as Integer is 2
Constant SIDE_EFFECT_IO as Integer is 4
Constant SIDE_EFFECT_EXCEPTION as Integer is 8
Constant SIDE_EFFECT_EXTERNAL_CALL as Integer is 16
Constant SIDE_EFFECT_GLOBAL_STATE as Integer is 32

Note: Escape status constants
Constant ESCAPE_NONE as Integer is 0
Constant ESCAPE_PARAMETER as Integer is 1
Constant ESCAPE_RETURN as Integer is 2
Constant ESCAPE_GLOBAL as Integer is 3
Constant ESCAPE_EXTERNAL as Integer is 4

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Phase 1: Initialization Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
create_whole_program_analysis initializes the main WPA structure.
All collections are initialized as empty and will be populated during analysis.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_whole_program_analysis" that takes mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate WholeProgramAnalysis (168 bytes — P1-E v3 layout)
    Let wpa be proc memory_allocate from Layout with WPA_STRUCT_SIZE

    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize all fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0, mir
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8, 0 Note: call_graph (will be built)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 16, List.create( )            Note: entry_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24, Set.create( )             Note: reachable_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 32, Set.create( )             Note: unreachable_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40, Dictionary.create( )      Note: type_hierarchy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 48, 0 Note: type_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 56, Dictionary.create( )      Note: escape_info
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64, Dictionary.create( )      Note: side_effect_info
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 72, Set.create( )             Note: pure_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 80, Set.create( )             Note: const_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88, Set.create( )             Note: exported_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96, Set.create( )             Note: address_taken_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104, List.create( )           Note: devirtualization_candidates
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 112, List.create( )           Note: inlining_candidates
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 120, Set.create( )            Note: constant_globals
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 128, 0                        Note: dce_plan (NEW, allocated by identify_whole_program_dce)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 136, Dictionary.create( )     Note: optimization_priorities (NEW)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 144, 0                        Note: points_to_map (lazily allocated by get_points_to_set on first use)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 152, List.create( )           Note: constant_prop_candidates (NEW)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 160, List.create( )           Note: specialization_candidates (NEW)

    Return wpa
End Process

@Reasoning
destroy_whole_program_analysis performs deep-clean tear-down of every
sub-resource owned by the WPA struct per CEO ratification. The deep-clean
contract releases:
  - All Set/Dict/List containers held at offsets 16, 24, 32, 40, 56, 64,
    72, 80, 88, 96, 104, 112, 120, 136, 144, 152, 160.
  - Per-candidate struct allocations in devirtualization_candidates,
    constant_prop_candidates, specialization_candidates.
  - The DCEPlan struct at offset 128 and its inner List handles.
  - The points_to_map Dictionary at offset 144 plus each List it caches.
  - The WPA block itself.

Shallow-cleaning would leak ~|MIR|/100 candidate structs (40 bytes each
for devirt, 24 for CP, 32 for spec) plus the DCEPlan and its three Lists
per compile. Across a 1000-source-file build that compounds to several
megabytes of avoidable leak. Deep-clean keeps the LTO subsystem within
the per-job arena budget.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Order matters: free the per-candidate structs FIRST (while the
container List still has handles to them), then free the container,
then free the WPA block last. Type-hierarchy nodes and method-info
records are owned by build_type_hierarchy_graph; this destructor
walks the type_hierarchy Dictionary and releases each TypeHierarchyNode
plus its inner virtual_methods Dictionary entries. IPA records owned
by compute_side_effects are walked the same way (side_effect_info
values are 96-byte InterProceduralInfo structs).

Set/Dict/List release uses the canonical destroy primitives. Each
primitive itself frees its internal arrays (the v0.0.8.5 collections
primitives are heap-backed; their destroy methods return the
underlying allocation to the heap free list).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Called exactly once per compile job at the end of optimize_program.
The cost is O(|candidates| + |MIR|) — linear in the total amount of
work the WPA pipeline performed. For a 10k-function program, the
tear-down typically takes <2ms (a small fraction of WPA's own build
time). The bulk cost is the per-candidate memory_deallocate calls;
no nested loops, no hash recomputation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. No untrusted data. The Process accepts the WPA
pointer returned by create_whole_program_analysis; callers must NOT
double-free (the WPA block is single-ownership owned-heap per the
v0.0.8.5 memory tiers). Returns 0 on null input as a defensive guard.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_whole_program_analysis" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1 — release per-candidate structs in devirtualization_candidates
    Let devirt_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104
    If devirt_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let dc_count be proc length from List with devirt_candidates
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than dc_count:
            Let candidate be proc get from List with devirt_candidates, i
            If candidate is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_deallocate from Layout with candidate
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with devirt_candidates
    End If

    Note: Step 2 — release per-candidate structs in constant_prop_candidates
    Let cp_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 152
    If cp_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let cp_count be proc length from List with cp_candidates
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than cp_count:
            Let cp_entry be proc get from List with cp_candidates, j
            If cp_entry is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_deallocate from Layout with cp_entry
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with cp_candidates
    End If

    Note: Step 3 — release per-candidate structs in specialization_candidates
    Let spec_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 160
    If spec_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let sc_count be proc length from List with spec_candidates
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than sc_count:
            Let sc_entry be proc get from List with spec_candidates, k
            If sc_entry is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_deallocate from Layout with sc_entry
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from List with spec_candidates
    End If

    Note: Step 4 — release DCEPlan and its three inner Lists
    Let dce_plan be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 128
    If dce_plan is not equal to 0:
        Let dead_funcs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 0
        If dead_funcs is not equal to 0:
            proc destroy from List with dead_funcs
        End If
        Let dead_globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 16
        If dead_globals is not equal to 0:
            proc destroy from List with dead_globals
        End If
        Let dead_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 32
        If dead_types is not equal to 0:
            proc destroy from List with dead_types
        End If
        proc memory_deallocate from Layout with dce_plan
    End If

    Note: Step 5 — release inlining_candidates List (entries owned by call_graph)
    Let inlining_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 112
    If inlining_candidates is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with inlining_candidates
    End If

    Note: Step 6 — release optimization_priorities Dict
    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 136
    If priorities is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dictionary with priorities
    End If

    Note: Step 6b — release points_to_map cache at offset 144. This cache is
    Note: lazily allocated by get_points_to_set; for compile jobs that never
    Note: trigger a points-to query the slot stays 0 and we skip cleanup. The
    Note: cache stores function-ID Lists keyed by value_id, so each entry is a
    Note: List that must be released before the Dictionary itself.
    Let points_to_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 144
    If points_to_map is not equal to 0:
        Let pts_keys be proc keys from Dictionary with points_to_map
        Let pts_key_count be proc length from List with pts_keys
        Let pk be 0
        While pk is less than pts_key_count:
            Let pts_value_id be proc get from List with pts_keys, pk
            Let pts_list be proc get from Dictionary with points_to_map, pts_value_id
            If pts_list is not equal to 0:
                proc destroy from List with pts_list
            End If
            Set pk to pk plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from Dictionary with points_to_map
    End If

    Note: Step 7 — release per-type TypeHierarchyNode + inner method_info records
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    If type_hierarchy is not equal to 0:
        Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
        Let th_count be proc length from List with type_ids
        Let t be 0
        While t is less than th_count:
            Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, t
            Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
            If type_node is not equal to 0:
                Note: parent_types, child_types, all_implementations are owned Lists/Sets
                Let parent_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 16
                If parent_types is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from List with parent_types
                End If
                Let child_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 32
                If child_types is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from List with child_types
                End If
                Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48
                If virtual_methods is not equal to 0:
                    Let method_names be proc keys from Dictionary with virtual_methods
                    Let mn_count be proc length from List with method_names
                    Let m be 0
                    While m is less than mn_count:
                        Let mname be proc get from List with method_names, m
                        Let method_info be proc get from Dictionary with virtual_methods, mname
                        If method_info is not equal to 0:
                            Let impls be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 24
                            If impls is not equal to 0:
                                proc destroy from List with impls
                            End If
                            proc memory_deallocate from Layout with method_info
                        End If
                        Set m to m plus 1
                    End While
                    proc destroy from Dictionary with virtual_methods
                End If
                Let all_impls be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 80
                If all_impls is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with all_impls
                End If
                proc memory_deallocate from Layout with type_node
            End If
            Set t to t plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    End If

    Note: Step 8 — release per-function InterProceduralInfo records and escape_info entries
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64
    If side_effect_info is not equal to 0:
        Let func_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with side_effect_info
        Let fi_count be proc length from List with func_ids
        Let fi be 0
        While fi is less than fi_count:
            Let function_id be proc get from List with func_ids, fi
            Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id
            If ipa_info is not equal to 0:
                Let esc_params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 8
                If esc_params is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with esc_params
                End If
                Let mem_reads be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 24
                If mem_reads is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with mem_reads
                End If
                Let mem_writes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 32
                If mem_writes is not equal to 0:
                    proc destroy from Set with mem_writes
                End If
                proc memory_deallocate from Layout with ipa_info
            End If
            Set fi to fi plus 1
        End While
        proc destroy from Dictionary with side_effect_info
    End If

    Note: Step 9 — release escape_info Dict (entries are small status integers, not owned structs)
    Let escape_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 56
    If escape_info is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dictionary with escape_info
    End If

    Note: Step 10 — release entry_functions list and the four function-ID Sets
    Let entry_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 16
    If entry_functions is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from List with entry_functions
    End If
    Let reachable_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    If reachable_functions is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with reachable_functions
    End If
    Let unreachable_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 32
    If unreachable_functions is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with unreachable_functions
    End If
    Let pure_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 72
    If pure_functions is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with pure_functions
    End If
    Let const_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 80
    If const_functions is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with const_functions
    End If
    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88
    If exported_functions is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with exported_functions
    End If
    Let address_taken_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96
    If address_taken_functions is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with address_taken_functions
    End If
    Let constant_globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 120
    If constant_globals is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Set with constant_globals
    End If

    Note: Step 11 — release the WPA struct itself
    proc memory_deallocate from Layout with wpa

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
initialize_wpa_from_mir is the main entry point for whole-program analysis.
It orchestrates all analysis phases in dependency order.

Analysis phases:
1. Build call graph (foundation)
2. Identify entry points
3. Compute reachability
4. Build type hierarchy
5. Perform IPA (escape, side effects, purity)
6. Compute visibility and devirtualization opportunities
@End Reasoning

Process called "initialize_wpa_from_mir" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If mir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Build whole-program call graph
    Let call_graph be build_whole_program_call_graph(wpa, mir)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8, call_graph

    Note: Phase 2: Identify entry points
    identify_entry_points(wpa, mir)

    Note: Phase 3: Compute global reachability from entry points
    compute_global_reachability(wpa)

    Note: Phase 4: Build type hierarchy
    build_type_hierarchy_graph(wpa, mir)

    Note: Phase 5: Analyze devirtualization opportunities
    compute_devirtualization_candidates(wpa)

    Note: Phase 6: Perform inter-procedural analysis
    compute_escape_analysis(wpa)
    compute_side_effects(wpa)
    compute_pure_functions(wpa)

    Note: Phase 7: Compute global visibility
    compute_global_visibility(wpa)

    Note: Phase 8a — Candidate-set generation (inlining, CP, specialization).
    Note: These populate the per-bucket candidate Lists that downstream phases
    Note: filter and rank. They do NOT depend on each other.
    identify_cross_module_inlining(wpa)
    identify_constant_propagation(wpa)
    identify_function_specialization(wpa)

    Note: Phase 8b — Reachability extraction. Depends on the E3-hardened
    Note: compute_global_reachability (Phase 3 above) having produced a sound
    Note: reachable_functions set covering exported, address-taken, indirect-target,
    Note: and virtual-dispatch-target functions.
    find_unreachable_functions(wpa)

    Note: Phase 8c — Devirtualization filter. Depends on the reachability set
    Note: from Phase 8b and the raw candidate List from Phase 5
    Note: (compute_devirtualization_candidates).
    identify_virtual_call_elimination(wpa)

    Note: Phase 8d — Aggregate DCE plan. Depends on the filtered devirt set
    Note: from Phase 8c because filtered candidates may keep functions alive
    Note: that the raw filter would have dropped.
    identify_whole_program_dce(wpa)

    Note: Phase 8e — Cross-bucket priority ranking. Depends on every candidate
    Note: List being final and the DCE plan being built.
    compute_optimization_priorities(wpa)

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_entry_points finds all program entry points.
Entry points include: main function, exported functions, global initializers.
These are the roots for reachability analysis.
@End Reasoning

Process called "identify_entry_points" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entry_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 16
    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88

    Note: Get all functions from MIR
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0
        Let function_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8

        Note: Check if function is exported (offset 24 in MIRFunction stores is_external flag)
        Note: For exported functions, we use a different marker in metadata
        Let is_exported be 0

        Note: Check function name for "main" entry point
        Let main_str be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with "main"
        Let is_main be proc string_equals from StringCore with function_name, main_str
        proc memory_deallocate from Layout with main_str

        If is_main is equal to 1:
            Note: Add main function as entry point
            proc append from List with entry_functions, function_id
            proc add from Set with exported_functions, function_id
            Set is_exported to 1
        End If

        Note: Check metadata for export annotation
        Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 88
        If metadata is not equal to 0:
            Note: Check if metadata indicates exported function
            Note: Metadata structure stores flags at offset 8
            Let flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata, 8
            Let export_flag be flags bitwise_and 1
            If export_flag is equal to 1:
                proc append from List with entry_functions, function_id
                proc add from Set with exported_functions, function_id
                Set is_exported to 1
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
create_interprocedural_info creates IPA info structure for a function.
All fields initialized to safe defaults (no escapes, no side effects).
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_interprocedural_info" that takes function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate InterProceduralInfo (96 bytes)
    Let ipa_info be proc memory_allocate from Layout with 96

    If ipa_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize all fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 0, function_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 8, Set.create( )         Note: escaping_parameters
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 16, 0 Note: escaping_returns = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 24, Set.create( )        Note: memory_reads
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 32, Set.create( )        Note: memory_writes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 40, 0 Note: indirect_reads = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 48, 0 Note: indirect_writes = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 56, 0 Note: calls_external = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 64, 0 Note: throws_exceptions = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 72, 1 Note: is_pure = true (proven otherwise)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 80, 1 Note: is_const = true (proven otherwise)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, SIDE_EFFECT_NONE Note: side_effect_flags = none

    Return ipa_info
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Phase 2: Call Graph Construction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
build_whole_program_call_graph builds the complete program call graph.
Uses existing call_graph.runa infrastructure but operates at whole-program scope.
@End Reasoning

Process called "build_whole_program_call_graph" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Use call_graph.runa's build_call_graph with null points-to analysis
    Note: Points-to analysis will be computed separately if needed
    Let call_graph be proc build_call_graph from CallGraph with mir, 0

    Note: Analyze indirect calls to resolve targets
    analyze_indirect_calls(wpa, call_graph, mir)

    Return call_graph
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_indirect_calls attempts to resolve indirect call targets.
Uses type information and control flow analysis to narrow possible targets.

Algorithm:
1. Get all unresolved indirect calls from call graph
2. For each call site, analyze the function pointer source
3. Use type constraints to determine possible target set
4. Add resolved edges to call graph
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_indirect_calls" that takes wpa as Integer, call_graph as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get indirect calls list from call graph
    Let indirect_calls be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_graph, 64
    Let indirect_count be proc length from List with indirect_calls

    Note: Get call graph nodes for updating
    Let cg_nodes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_graph, 0

    Note: For each indirect call, attempt resolution
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than indirect_count:
        Let call_site be proc get from List with indirect_calls, i

        Note: Get instruction pointer from call site
        Let inst_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 0

        Note: Get function pointer operand (operand1 for CALL_INDIRECT)
        Let func_ptr_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 16

        Note: Get caller function ID
        Let caller_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 8

        Note: Trace function pointer to find possible targets
        Let possible_targets be resolve_function_pointer(wpa, mir, func_ptr_value)
        Let target_count be proc length from List with possible_targets

        Note: Add call edges for each resolved target
        Let t be 0
        While t is less than target_count:
            Let target_func_id be proc get from List with possible_targets, t

            Note: Get or create caller node in call graph
            Let caller_node be proc get from Dictionary with cg_nodes, caller_id
            If caller_node is not equal to 0:
                Note: Add callee to caller's callee list
                Let callees be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with caller_node, 8
                If proc contains from Set with callees, target_func_id is equal to 0:
                    proc add from Set with callees, target_func_id

                    Note: Increment caller's out-degree
                    Let out_degree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with caller_node, 32
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with caller_node, 32, out_degree plus 1
                End If
            End If

            Note: Get or create callee node in call graph
            Let callee_node be proc get from Dictionary with cg_nodes, target_func_id
            If callee_node is not equal to 0:
                Note: Add caller to callee's caller list
                Let callers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_node, 16
                If proc contains from Set with callers, caller_id is equal to 0:
                    proc add from Set with callers, caller_id

                    Note: Increment callee's in-degree
                    Let in_degree be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_node, 40
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with callee_node, 40, in_degree plus 1
                End If
            End If

            Set t to t plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
resolve_function_pointer performs basic points-to analysis to resolve indirect calls.
Traces function pointer values through def-use chains to find possible targets.

Algorithm:
1. Get the defining instruction for the function pointer value
2. If CONST instruction: extract function address, return singleton set
3. If PHI node: recursively resolve all incoming values
4. If LOAD: could be from function pointer variable (conservative: return empty)
5. If parameter: unknown at compile time (conservative: return empty)
6. Otherwise: return empty set (unresolved)
@End Reasoning

Process called "resolve_function_pointer" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create empty result list
    Let result be proc create from List

    Note: Get all functions to find value definition
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Note: Search all functions for the value definition
    Let f be 0
    While f is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, f
        Let value_to_inst be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 64

        Note: Look up defining instruction
        Let def_inst be proc get from Dictionary with value_to_inst, value_id

        If def_inst is not equal to 0:
            Note: Found defining instruction - check its type
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 0

            Note: Check for CONST (20001) - function address constant
            If opcode is equal to 20001:
                Note: operand1 contains the function ID
                Let target_func_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
                If target_func_id is not equal to 0:
                    proc append from List with result, target_func_id
                End If
            End If

            Note: Check for PHI (20300) - merge point, recursively resolve
            If opcode is equal to 20300:
                Note: PHI has multiple incoming values in metadata
                Note: For simplicity, we extract operands (could have more sophisticated PHI handling)
                Let incoming1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
                Let incoming2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 24
                Let incoming3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 32

                If incoming1 is not equal to 0:
                    Let targets1 be resolve_function_pointer(wpa, mir, incoming1)
                    Let count1 be proc length from List with targets1
                    Let k be 0
                    While k is less than count1:
                        proc append from List with result, List.get(targets1, k )
                        Set k to k plus 1
                    End While
                End If

                If incoming2 is not equal to 0:
                    Let targets2 be resolve_function_pointer(wpa, mir, incoming2)
                    Let count2 be proc length from List with targets2
                    Set k to 0
                    While k is less than count2:
                        proc append from List with result, List.get(targets2, k )
                        Set k to k plus 1
                    End While
                End If

                If incoming3 is not equal to 0:
                    Let targets3 be resolve_function_pointer(wpa, mir, incoming3)
                    Let count3 be proc length from List with targets3
                    Set k to 0
                    While k is less than count3:
                        proc append from List with result, List.get(targets3, k )
                        Set k to k plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If

            Note: Handle LOAD (20200) - load from memory location
            If opcode is equal to 20200:
                Note: Get memory address being loaded from
                Let addr_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16

                Note: Check if loading from global function pointer variable
                Let points_to_set be get_points_to_set(wpa, addr_value)
                Let pts_count be proc length from List with points_to_set

                Set k to 0
                While k is less than pts_count:
                    Let target be proc get from List with points_to_set, k
                    proc append from List with result, target
                    Set k to k plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Handle ADDRESS_OF (20150) - taking address of function
            If opcode is equal to 20150:
                Note: operand1 contains the entity whose address is taken
                Let target_entity be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16

                Note: Check if it's a function address
                Let entity_type be get_entity_type(mir, target_entity)
                If entity_type is equal to 1:  Note: Function entity
                    proc append from List with result, target_entity
                End If
            End If

            Note: Handle PARAMETER (20100) - function parameter
            If opcode is equal to 20100:
                Note: Function parameters could point to any function passed as argument
                Note: Use interprocedural analysis to determine possible values
                Let param_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
                Let param_targets be analyze_parameter_targets(wpa, mir, value_id, param_index)
                Let pt_count be proc length from List with param_targets

                Set k to 0
                While k is less than pt_count:
                    proc append from List with result, List.get(param_targets, k )
                    Set k to k plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Found definition, stop searching
            Return result
        End If

        Set f to f plus 1
    End While

    Note: No definition found - return empty set
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_global_reachability is the E3-hardened reachability fixpoint used
by find_unreachable_functions and the DCE plan builder. A simple DFS that
follows only direct callees is unsound in any program that uses indirect
or virtual dispatch: address-taken functions, function-pointer table
entries, and overridden virtual methods would all be misclassified as
dead even though the runtime can branch into them. The E3 design (see
designs/P1-E-wpa-dce-devirt-design-v3.md §5) closes that hole with five
edge-type predicates, all evaluated during the same worklist traversal:

  P-EXP — exported worklist seed. Every function in
          wpa.exported_functions enters the worklist as a root, because
          the linker / FFI / module boundary can invoke it from outside
          the translation unit.

  P-AT  — address-taken worklist seed. Every function in
          wpa.address_taken_functions enters the worklist as a root,
          because any reachable code can call it through a captured
          pointer.

  P-DIR — direct callee edge. For every CallSite with callee_id != 0,
          add callee_id to the worklist (the original DFS behaviour,
          preserved unchanged).

  P-VIRT — virtual dispatch edge. For every CallSite with call_type ==
           CALL_TYPE_VIRTUAL (=2), the callee_id names the dispatched
           method but the runtime target may be ANY implementation
           registered against the method in the type hierarchy. Every
           such implementation is added to the worklist via
           all_implementations_of_method.

  P-IND — indirect call edge. For every CallSite with callee_id == 0
          (i.e. CALL_TYPE_INDIRECT), the function-pointer value lives
          at offset 16 of the MIR instruction. Resolve every possible
          target via resolve_function_pointer (which itself relies on
          the points-to cache at wpa[144]) and add each to the
          worklist.

After the worklist drains, any function in the call graph that was not
added to wpa.reachable_functions is added to wpa.unreachable_functions.
The combined P-EXP/P-AT seeding plus P-DIR/P-VIRT/P-IND edge expansion
is the soundness foundation that find_unreachable_functions later
verifies (a reachable set that fails to include every exported or
address-taken function indicates a bug in this pass, and
find_unreachable_functions returns -1 to refuse the DCE plan).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Initialise:
  1. Load call_graph, entry_functions, reachable Set, unreachable Set,
     exported Set, address_taken Set, type_hierarchy, and mir from the
     WPA struct.
  2. Seed the worklist with entry_functions (P-EXP/P-AT roots are added
     immediately after to keep all roots at the front of the worklist
     before traversal begins).

Worklist traversal (FIFO; behaviour is identical for FIFO/LIFO because
this is a reachability fixpoint, not a path-sensitive walk):
  3. Pop current_id from the worklist.
  4. If reachable already contains current_id, continue (cycle guard).
  5. Add current_id to reachable.
  6. Look up the CallGraphNode at cg_nodes[current_id]; if none, the
     function has no outgoing edges (leaf), continue.
  7. For each CallSite in node.call_sites:
       a. P-DIR: if callee_id != 0 and not in reachable, append to
          worklist.
       b. P-VIRT: if call_type == 2, enumerate implementations via
          all_implementations_of_method(type_hierarchy, callee_id) and
          append each not-yet-reachable implementation.
       c. P-IND: if callee_id == 0, read the function-pointer value
          from inst[offset 16] and call resolve_function_pointer(wpa,
          mir, func_ptr_value); append every returned target not yet
          in reachable.

Finalise:
  8. Iterate every key in cg_nodes (the complete function-ID universe).
     Any function-ID not in reachable is added to unreachable.
  9. Return 1.

Returns 1 unconditionally on success; soundness verification is
deferred to find_unreachable_functions which audits the resulting
reachable Set against the exported and address-taken predicate sets.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Worklist traversal is O(|callsites|) amortised: every CallGraphNode
is processed at most once thanks to the reachable-Set cycle guard, and
each CallSite contributes a constant amount of work plus (for P-VIRT
sites) the length of the implementation list. P-IND adds the cost of
one resolve_function_pointer query per indirect site, which is
memoised through the points_to_map at wpa[144]; cold misses traverse
compute_points_to_for_value over the defining MIR function. For a
10k-function program with typical (~5%) indirect-dispatch density the
whole pass completes in single-digit milliseconds on x86_64.

The seeding loops over exported and address_taken Sets are O(|S|);
for typical programs these contain a few hundred entries.

The final unreachable-set construction is O(|cg_nodes|) — one Set
contains-check per function ID, all sub-millisecond.

Memory: the worklist is a single List that grows to at most the union
of all enqueued IDs (bounded by |cg_nodes|); the reachable / unreachable
Sets are pre-allocated by create_whole_program_analysis. No additional
per-call allocations beyond those owned by resolve_function_pointer.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. The pass operates on already-parsed MIR plus the
WPA-owned call graph and type hierarchy; no untrusted input is read.

Soundness is the only security-relevant invariant: an UNDER-approximation
of reachability would let DCE delete code that is in fact callable,
producing a miscompiled binary. The E3 predicates exist specifically to
prevent that:
  - Omitting P-EXP would delete every exported entry point not invoked
    internally.
  - Omitting P-AT would delete every function whose address escapes
    via globals, struct fields, or closures.
  - Omitting P-VIRT would delete every overridden method not invoked
    through a direct CALL.
  - Omitting P-IND would delete every callback dispatched through a
    function-pointer parameter.

OVER-approximation (treating a function as reachable when it isn't) is
safe — it merely defeats DCE for that function. find_unreachable_functions
runs after this pass and rejects the build (returns -1, the DCE plan is
not produced) if the verification predicates detect that any exported
or address-taken function failed to be marked reachable, providing a
fail-safe.

No locking required: this Process runs single-threaded within the WPA
phase pipeline. resolve_function_pointer is recursive but bounded by
the points-to cache; runaway recursion is impossible because each call
checks the cache before re-entering.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_global_reachability" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Let entry_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 16
    Let reachable be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    Let unreachable be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 32
    Let exported be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88
    Let address_taken be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0

    Note: Get all functions from call graph
    Let cg_nodes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_graph, 0
    Let all_function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with cg_nodes

    Note: Initialize worklist with entry points
    Let worklist be proc create from List
    Let entry_count be proc length from List with entry_functions

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let entry_id be proc get from List with entry_functions, i
        proc append from List with worklist, entry_id
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: P-EXP — seed worklist with exported functions (callable from outside
    Note: the translation unit). Exported functions are reachable by definition
    Note: even if no internal call exists.
    If exported is not equal to 0:
        Let exp_list be proc to_list from Set with exported
        Let exp_count be proc length from List with exp_list
        Let e be 0
        While e is less than exp_count:
            Let exp_id be proc get from List with exp_list, e
            proc append from List with worklist, exp_id
            Set e to e plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: P-AT — seed worklist with address-taken functions. A function whose
    Note: address is captured into a function-pointer global, struct field, or
    Note: closure can be invoked through indirect/virtual dispatch from any
    Note: reachable function and must therefore be conservatively treated as
    Note: reachable from the program's root set.
    If address_taken is not equal to 0:
        Let at_list be proc to_list from Set with address_taken
        Let at_count be proc length from List with at_list
        Let a be 0
        While a is less than at_count:
            Let at_id be proc get from List with at_list, a
            proc append from List with worklist, at_id
            Set a to a plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: DFS traversal from entry points and seeded predicate sets.
    While proc length from List with worklist is greater than 0:
        Note: Pop front
        Let current_id be proc get from List with worklist, 0
        proc remove_at from List with worklist, 0

        Note: Skip if already visited
        Let already_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable, current_id
        If already_reachable is equal to 1:
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Mark as reachable
        proc add from Set with reachable, current_id

        Note: Get callees from call graph
        Let node be proc get from Dictionary with cg_nodes, current_id
        If node is not equal to 0:
            Let call_sites be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
            Let call_site_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24

            Let j be 0
            While j is less than call_site_count:
                Let call_site be proc get from List with call_sites, j
                Let callee_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 8
                Let call_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 16

                If callee_id is not equal to 0:
                    Note: P-DIR — direct call edge. Original behavior preserved.
                    Let callee_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable, callee_id
                    If callee_reachable is equal to 0:
                        proc append from List with worklist, callee_id
                    End If

                    Note: P-VIRT — if the call type is CALL_TYPE_VIRTUAL, the
                    Note: callee_id names the dispatched method but the runtime
                    Note: target may be any implementation. Enumerate every
                    Note: implementation registered in the type hierarchy and
                    Note: add it to the worklist.
                    If call_type is equal to 2:
                        Let impls be all_implementations_of_method(type_hierarchy, callee_id)
                        If impls is not equal to 0:
                            Let impc be proc length from List with impls
                            Let m be 0
                            While m is less than impc:
                                Let impl_id be proc get from List with impls, m
                                If impl_id is not equal to 0:
                                    Let impl_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable, impl_id
                                    If impl_reachable is equal to 0:
                                        proc append from List with worklist, impl_id
                                    End If
                                End If
                                Set m to m plus 1
                            End While
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If callee_id is equal to 0:
                    Note: P-IND — indirect call edge. Resolve the function-pointer
                    Note: value through points-to analysis and follow every
                    Note: possible target. The instruction's func_ptr_value lives
                    Note: at offset 16 of the MIR instruction (same convention
                    Note: used by compute_devirtualization_candidates).
                    Let inst be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 0
                    If inst is not equal to 0:
                        Let func_ptr_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                        Let possible_targets be resolve_function_pointer(wpa, mir, func_ptr_value)
                        If possible_targets is not equal to 0:
                            Let ptc be proc length from List with possible_targets
                            Let p be 0
                            While p is less than ptc:
                                Let pt be proc get from List with possible_targets, p
                                If pt is not equal to 0:
                                    Let pt_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable, pt
                                    If pt_reachable is equal to 0:
                                        proc append from List with worklist, pt
                                    End If
                                End If
                                Set p to p plus 1
                            End While
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End While

    Note: All functions not in reachable set are unreachable
    Let all_count be proc length from List with all_function_ids
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than all_count:
        Let function_id be proc get from List with all_function_ids, i
        Let is_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable, function_id
        If is_reachable is equal to 0:
            proc add from Set with unreachable, function_id
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Phase 3: Type Hierarchy Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
build_type_hierarchy_graph constructs the complete type hierarchy.
Maps all types in the program and their inheritance/implementation relationships.

Algorithm:
1. Collect all types from MIR type table
2. For each type, create TypeHierarchyNode
3. Analyze inheritance and interface implementation
4. Build parent-child relationships
5. Identify virtual methods and override chains
@End Reasoning

Process called "build_type_hierarchy_graph" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40

    Note: Get type table from MIR
    Let type_table be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 48
    If type_table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Type table is Dictionary mapping type_id -> HIRTypeInfo
    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_table
    Let type_count be proc length from List with type_ids

    Note: Phase 1: Create nodes for all types
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than type_count:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Let type_info be proc get from Dictionary with type_table, type_id

        Note: Create type hierarchy node
        Let type_node be create_type_hierarchy_node(type_id, type_info)
        proc set from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id, type_node

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Update type count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 48, type_count

    Note: Phase 2: Build parent-child relationships
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than type_count:
        Set type_id to proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Set type_node to proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
        Set type_info to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 8

        Note: Get base types from HIRTypeInfo (offset 72)
        Let base_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_info, 72
        If base_types is not equal to 0:
            Let base_count be proc length from List with base_types

            Let j be 0
            While j is less than base_count:
                Let base_type_id be proc get from List with base_types, j

                Note: Add to parent types
                Let parent_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 16
                proc append from List with parent_types, base_type_id

                Note: Increment parent count
                Let parent_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 24
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_node, 24, parent_count plus 1

                Note: Add this type to parent's child types
                Let parent_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, base_type_id
                If parent_node is not equal to 0:
                    Let child_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node, 32
                    proc append from List with child_types, type_id

                    Let child_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node, 40
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent_node, 40, child_count plus 1
                End If

                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Phase 3: Identify virtual methods
    identify_virtual_methods(wpa, mir)

    Note: Phase 4: Compute override chains
    compute_override_chains(wpa)

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
create_type_hierarchy_node creates a type hierarchy node for a type.
Initializes all collections as empty.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_type_hierarchy_node" that takes type_id as Integer, type_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate TypeHierarchyNode (88 bytes)
    Let node be proc memory_allocate from Layout with 88

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, type_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, type_info
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, List.create( )           Note: parent_types
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0 Note: parent_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, List.create( )           Note: child_types
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0 Note: child_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, Dictionary.create( )     Note: virtual_methods
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 56, 0 Note: method_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 64, 0 Note: is_sealed = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 72, 0 Note: is_abstract = false
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 80, Set.create( )            Note: all_implementations

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_virtual_methods finds all virtual methods in all types.
Virtual methods are methods that can be overridden in derived types.

Algorithm:
1. For each type in hierarchy
2. Get all methods from type
3. Check if method is virtual (can be overridden)
4. Create MethodInfo for each virtual method
5. Store in type's virtual_methods dictionary
@End Reasoning

Process called "identify_virtual_methods" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    Let type_count be proc length from List with type_ids

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than type_count:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
        Let type_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 8

        Note: Get methods from HIRTypeInfo
        Note: Methods stored at offset 80 in HIRTypeInfo
        Let methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_info, 80
        If methods is not equal to 0:
            Let method_count be proc length from List with methods

            Let j be 0
            While j is less than method_count:
                Let method_symbol be proc get from List with methods, j

                Note: Check if method is virtual
                Note: Method flags at offset 16 in method symbol
                Let method_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_symbol, 16
                Let is_virtual be method_flags bitwise_and 1

                If is_virtual is equal to 1:
                    Note: Create MethodInfo
                    Let method_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_symbol, 0
                    Let method_sig be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_symbol, 8

                    Let method_info be proc memory_allocate from Layout with 64
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 0, method_name
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 8, method_sig
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 16, type_id
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 24, List.create( )  Note: implementations
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 32, 0 Note: implementation_count
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 40, 0 Note: is_final
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 48, 0 Note: is_abstract
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 56, 0 Note: unique_implementation

                    Note: Add to type's virtual methods
                    Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48
                    proc set from Dictionary with virtual_methods, method_name, method_info

                    Note: Increment method count
                    Let vm_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 56
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with type_node, 56, vm_count plus 1
                End If

                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_override_chains analyzes method override relationships.
Determines which methods override which base class methods.

Algorithm:
1. For each type in hierarchy
2. For each virtual method in type
3. Check all parent types for method with same signature
4. If found, this is an override - link them
5. Track all implementations for devirtualization
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_override_chains" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    Let type_count be proc length from List with type_ids

    Note: For each type, analyze its virtual methods
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than type_count:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id

        Note: Get parent types
        Let parent_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 16
        Let parent_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 24

        Note: Get this type's virtual methods
        Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48
        Let method_names be proc keys from Dictionary with virtual_methods
        Let method_count be proc length from List with method_names

        Note: For each method, check if it overrides parent method
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than method_count:
            Let method_name be proc get from List with method_names, j
            Let method_info be proc get from Dictionary with virtual_methods, method_name

            Note: Check all parent types for same method
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than parent_count:
                Let parent_type_id be proc get from List with parent_types, k
                Let parent_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, parent_type_id

                If parent_node is not equal to 0:
                    Let parent_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_node, 48
                    Let parent_method_info be proc get from Dictionary with parent_methods, method_name

                    If parent_method_info is not equal to 0:
                        Note: Found override relationship
                        Note: Add this method to parent's implementations list
                        Let implementations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_method_info, 24
                        Let method_func_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 56
                        proc append from List with implementations, method_func_id

                        Note: Increment implementation count
                        Let impl_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent_method_info, 32
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parent_method_info, 32, impl_count plus 1
                    End If
                End If

                Set k to k plus 1
            End While

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_method_implementations finds all concrete implementations of methods.
This is critical for devirtualization analysis.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_method_implementations" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    Let type_count be proc length from List with type_ids

    Note: Get all functions from MIR
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Note: Build mapping of method_name -> function_id
    Let method_to_function be proc create from Dictionary

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0
        Let function_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8

        Note: Add to mapping
        proc set from Dictionary with method_to_function, function_name, function_id

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: For each type's virtual methods, find implementations
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than type_count:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
        Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48
        Let method_names be proc keys from Dictionary with virtual_methods
        Let method_count be proc length from List with method_names

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than method_count:
            Let method_name be proc get from List with method_names, j
            Let method_info be proc get from Dictionary with virtual_methods, method_name

            Note: Look up function ID for this method
            Set function_id to proc get from Dictionary with method_to_function, method_name
            If function_id is not equal to 0:
                Note: Found implementation
                Let implementations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 24
                proc append from List with implementations, function_id

                Note: Increment implementation count
                Let impl_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 32
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 32, impl_count plus 1
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
find_unique_implementations identifies methods with exactly one implementation.
These are candidates for devirtualization.
@End Reasoning

Process called "find_unique_implementations" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    Let type_count be proc length from List with type_ids

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than type_count:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
        Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48
        Let method_names be proc keys from Dictionary with virtual_methods
        Let method_count be proc length from List with method_names

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than method_count:
            Let method_name be proc get from List with method_names, j
            Let method_info be proc get from Dictionary with virtual_methods, method_name

            Note: Check implementation count
            Let impl_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 32
            If impl_count is equal to 1:
                Note: Unique implementation - can devirtualize
                Let implementations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 24
                Let unique_impl be proc get from List with implementations, 0
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with method_info, 56, unique_impl
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_devirtualization_candidates finds virtual call sites that can be devirtualized.
A virtual call can be devirtualized if the target method has exactly one implementation.

Algorithm:
1. Scan all function bodies for virtual call instructions
2. For each virtual call, determine the method being called
3. Look up method in type hierarchy
4. If method has unique implementation, mark as devirtualizable
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_devirtualization_candidates" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let devirt_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40

    Note: First, find unique implementations
    find_unique_implementations(wpa)

    Note: Get all functions from MIR
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Note: Scan all functions for virtual calls
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 16

        If cfg is not equal to 0:
            Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 0
            Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

            Let b be 0
            While b is less than block_count:
                Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
                Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

                Let j be 0
                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

                    Note: Check for virtual calls (MIR_CALL_INDIRECT = 20305)
                    If opcode is equal to 20305:
                        Note: Use points-to analysis to determine possible targets
                        Let func_ptr_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16

                        Note: Resolve function pointer to possible targets
                        Let possible_targets be resolve_function_pointer(wpa, mir, func_ptr_value)
                        Let target_count be proc length from List with possible_targets

                        Note: If exactly one target, devirtualizable
                        If target_count is equal to 1:
                            Let target_func be proc get from List with possible_targets, 0

                            Note: Create canonical 40-byte devirtualization candidate
                            Note: (P1-E v3 E1 — single producer shape for all paths).
                            Let candidate be proc allocate from Layout with DEVIRT_CANDIDATE_SIZE
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 0, inst        Note: Call site
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 8, target_func Note: Target function
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 16, 1          Note: confidence = 1 (exact)
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 24, 0          Note: verified = false (set by identify_virtual_call_elimination)
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 32, 0          Note: is_speculative = 0 (exact)

                            Note: Add to candidates list
                            proc append from List with devirt_candidates, candidate
                        End If

                        Note: If multiple targets but one is dominant, record as speculative
                        If target_count is greater than 1:
                            Note: Analyze call site frequency to determine dominant target
                            Let dominant_target be find_dominant_target(possible_targets, inst)

                            If dominant_target is not equal to 0:
                                Note: Create speculative devirtualization candidate (40 bytes canonical)
                                Set candidate to proc allocate from Layout with DEVIRT_CANDIDATE_SIZE
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 0, inst
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 8, dominant_target
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 16, 0      Note: confidence = 0 (speculative)
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 24, 0      Note: verified = false
                                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 32, 1      Note: is_speculative = 1

                                proc append from List with devirt_candidates, candidate
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Note: Check for direct calls to virtual methods
                    If opcode is equal to 20304:
                        Let callee_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16

                        Note: Look up callee function to get its name
                        Set functions to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
                        Let callee_func be proc get from Dictionary with functions, callee_id

                        If callee_func is not equal to 0:
                            Note: Get function name (offset 0)
                            Let func_name be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_func, 0

                            Note: Search type hierarchy for this method name
                            Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
                            Let type_count_local be proc length from List with type_ids

                            Let t be 0
                            While t is less than type_count_local:
                                Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, t
                                Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
                                Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48

                                Note: Check if this method exists in this type's virtual methods
                                Let method_info be proc get from Dictionary with virtual_methods, func_name

                                If method_info is not equal to 0:
                                    Note: Check if unique implementation exists
                                    Let unique_impl be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 56

                                    If unique_impl is not equal to 0:
                                        Note: P1-E v3 E1 — emit the canonical 40-byte struct (not
                                        Note: a 2-element List). Eliminates the latent shape mismatch
                                        Note: that mark_devirtualizable_calls and apply_devirtualization
                                        Note: previously stumbled on.
                                        Set candidate to proc allocate from Layout with DEVIRT_CANDIDATE_SIZE
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 0, inst
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 8, unique_impl
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 16, 1   Note: confidence = exact
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 24, 0   Note: verified = false
                                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 32, 0   Note: is_speculative = 0
                                        proc append from List with devirt_candidates, candidate
                                    End If
                                End If

                                Set t to t plus 1
                            End While
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While

                Set b to b plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
mark_devirtualizable_calls marks virtual call sites for devirtualization.
Updates MIR instructions to indicate static resolution is possible.
@End Reasoning

Process called "mark_devirtualizable_calls" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let devirt_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104
    Let candidate_count be proc length from List with devirt_candidates

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than candidate_count:
        Note: Get canonical 40-byte DevirtCandidate struct (P1-E v3 E1).
        Let candidate be proc get from List with devirt_candidates, i

        Note: Extract instruction pointer at offset 0 and target_func_id at offset 8.
        Note: Both producer sites in compute_devirtualization_candidates emit
        Note: the canonical struct shape; identify_virtual_call_elimination's
        Note: normalize_devirt_candidates pass guarantees this layout regardless
        Note: of producer.
        Let inst_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 0
        Let target_func_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 8

        Note: Mark instruction with devirtualization metadata.
        Note: MIRNode metadata field is at offset 64 (8 fields * 8 bytes).
        Note: Store target_func_id as metadata to indicate devirtualization target.
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 64, target_func_id

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Phase 4: Inter-procedural Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
compute_escape_analysis performs whole-program escape analysis.
Determines which values escape their allocation context.

A value escapes if:
- It is stored to a global variable
- It is returned from a function
- It is passed to an external function
- Its address is taken and stored in escaping location

Algorithm:
1. Initialize all values as non-escaping
2. Scan all functions for escape-inducing operations
3. Propagate escape information through call graph
4. Fixed-point iteration until no changes
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_escape_analysis" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let escape_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 56
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64

    Note: Get all functions
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Note: For each function, create IPA info and analyze escapes
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0

        Note: Create IPA info for function
        Let ipa_info be create_interprocedural_info(function_id)
        proc set from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id, ipa_info

        Note: Analyze parameter escapes
        analyze_parameter_escape(wpa, mir_func, ipa_info)

        Note: Analyze return escapes
        analyze_return_escape(wpa, mir_func, ipa_info)

        Note: Analyze field escapes
        analyze_field_escape(wpa, mir_func, ipa_info)

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_parameter_escape checks if function parameters escape.
A parameter escapes if it is stored, returned, or passed to escaping context.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_parameter_escape" that takes wpa as Integer, mir_func as Integer, ipa_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Let escaping_params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 8

    Note: Get function parameters
    Let parameters be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 16
    Let param_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 24

    Note: Get function body CFG
    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Note: Scan all instructions for parameter uses
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

            Note: Check for STORE operations (20201)
            If opcode is equal to 20201:
                Note: Store may cause escape
                Let value_operand be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16

                Note: Check if value is a parameter
                Let p be 0
                While p is less than param_count:
                    Let param_value_id be proc get from List with parameters, p
                    If param_value_id is equal to value_operand:
                        Note: Parameter escapes via store
                        proc add from Set with escaping_params, p
                    End If
                    Set p to p plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Check for RETURN operations (20303)
            If opcode is equal to 20303:
                Let return_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16

                Set p to 0
                While p is less than param_count:
                    Set param_value_id to proc get from List with parameters, p
                    If param_value_id is equal to return_value:
                        Note: Parameter escapes via return
                        proc add from Set with escaping_params, p
                    End If
                    Set p to p plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Check for CALL operations (20304, 20305)
            If opcode is equal to 20304:
                Note: Check if any parameters match call arguments
                Let arg1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                Let arg2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 24
                Let arg3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 32

                Set p to 0
                While p is less than param_count:
                    Set param_value_id to proc get from List with parameters, p
                    If param_value_id is equal to arg1:
                        proc add from Set with escaping_params, p
                    End If
                    If param_value_id is equal to arg2:
                        proc add from Set with escaping_params, p
                    End If
                    If param_value_id is equal to arg3:
                        proc add from Set with escaping_params, p
                    End If
                    Set p to p plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_return_escape checks if function return value escapes.
Return values always escape to caller context.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_return_escape" that takes wpa as Integer, mir_func as Integer, ipa_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Note: Scan for RETURN instructions
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

            Note: Check for RETURN (20303)
            If opcode is equal to 20303:
                Let return_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                If return_value is not equal to 0:
                    Note: Function returns a value - mark as escaping
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 16, 1
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_field_escape checks if values escape via field stores.
Storing to an object field may cause escape if object escapes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_field_escape" that takes wpa as Integer, mir_func as Integer, ipa_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Note: Scan for STORE_FIELD instructions
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

            Note: Check for STORE_FIELD (20204)
            If opcode is equal to 20204:
                Note: Field store - check if object escapes
                Let object be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 24

                Note: Flow-sensitive escape analysis
                Note: Value escapes if object escapes OR object is heap-allocated global

                Note: Check if object is a parameter (parameters escape by definition)
                Let object_def be get_value_definition(mir_func, object)
                Let object_opcode be 0
                If object_def is not equal to 0:
                    Set object_opcode to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with object_def, 0
                End If

                Note: If object is parameter (20100) or global (20002), value escapes
                If object_opcode is equal to 20100:
                    Note: Storing to parameter - value escapes to caller
                    mark_value_as_escaping(ipa_info, value)
                End If

                If object_opcode is equal to 20002:
                    Note: Storing to global - value escapes globally
                    mark_value_as_escaping(ipa_info, value)
                End If

                Note: Check if object is allocated on heap (ALLOC instruction)
                If object_opcode is equal to 20250:
                    Note: Heap allocation - check if allocation escapes
                    Let alloc_escapes be check_allocation_escapes(wpa, mir_func, object_def)
                    If alloc_escapes is equal to 1:
                        mark_value_as_escaping(ipa_info, value)
                    End If
                End If

                Note: Check if object points to escaping location
                Let object_pts be get_points_to_set(wpa, object)
                Let pts_count be proc length from List with object_pts
                If pts_count is greater than 0:
                    Note: Object has points-to targets - check if any escape
                    Let k be 0
                    While k is less than pts_count:
                        Let target be proc get from List with object_pts, k
                        Let target_escapes be check_value_escapes(ipa_info, target)
                        If target_escapes is equal to 1:
                            mark_value_as_escaping(ipa_info, value)
                        End If
                        Set k to k plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_side_effects analyzes what effects each function has.
Side effects include: memory reads/writes, I/O, exceptions, global state mutation.

Algorithm:
1. For each function, scan all instructions
2. Classify instructions by effect type
3. Mark memory operations, calls, I/O operations
4. Propagate effects through call graph
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_side_effects" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64

    Note: Get all functions
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Note: For each function, analyze side effects
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0

        Note: Get IPA info for function
        Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id
        If ipa_info is equal to 0:
            Set ipa_info to create_interprocedural_info(function_id)
            proc set from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id, ipa_info
        End If

        Note: Analyze memory effects
        analyze_memory_effects(wpa, mir_func, ipa_info)

        Note: Analyze control flow effects
        analyze_control_flow_effects(wpa, mir_func, ipa_info)

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_memory_effects checks what memory locations a function accesses.
Tracks reads, writes, indirect accesses through pointers.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_memory_effects" that takes wpa as Integer, mir_func as Integer, ipa_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Let memory_reads be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 24
    Let memory_writes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 32
    Let side_effect_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88

    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

            Note: Check for LOAD (20200)
            If opcode is equal to 20200:
                Set side_effect_flags to side_effect_flags bitwise_or SIDE_EFFECT_MEMORY_READ
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, side_effect_flags
            End If

            Note: Check for STORE (20201)
            If opcode is equal to 20201:
                Set side_effect_flags to side_effect_flags bitwise_or SIDE_EFFECT_MEMORY_WRITE
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, side_effect_flags
            End If

            Note: Check for LOAD_FIELD (20203)
            If opcode is equal to 20203:
                Set side_effect_flags to side_effect_flags bitwise_or SIDE_EFFECT_MEMORY_READ
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, side_effect_flags
            End If

            Note: Check for STORE_FIELD (20204)
            If opcode is equal to 20204:
                Set side_effect_flags to side_effect_flags bitwise_or SIDE_EFFECT_MEMORY_WRITE
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, side_effect_flags
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_control_flow_effects checks for exceptional control flow.
Tracks exceptions, external calls, other non-local control flow.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_control_flow_effects" that takes wpa as Integer, mir_func as Integer, ipa_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Let side_effect_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88

    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

            Note: Check for THROW (20703)
            If opcode is equal to 20703:
                Set side_effect_flags to side_effect_flags bitwise_or SIDE_EFFECT_EXCEPTION
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 64, 1 Note: throws_exceptions
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, side_effect_flags
            End If

            Note: Check for CALL to external function (20304)
            If opcode is equal to 20304:
                Let callee_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16

                Note: Look up callee function to check if external
                Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
                Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
                Let callee_func be proc get from Dictionary with functions, callee_id

                If callee_func is not equal to 0:
                    Note: Check is_external field (offset 80)
                    Let is_external be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_func, 80

                    If is_external is equal to 1:
                        Set side_effect_flags to side_effect_flags bitwise_or SIDE_EFFECT_EXTERNAL_CALL
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 56, 1 Note: calls_external
                        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, side_effect_flags
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_pure_functions identifies pure functions (no side effects, deterministic).
Pure functions can be eliminated if their results are unused.

A function is pure if:
- No memory writes
- No I/O operations
- No exceptions
- No external calls
- All called functions are also pure
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_pure_functions" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64
    Let pure_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 72
    Let const_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 80

    Note: Get all function IDs
    Let function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with side_effect_info
    Let function_count be proc length from List with function_ids

    Note: Optimistic initialization: add all functions, then remove impure ones
    Note: This is correct for fixed-point iteration
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let function_id be proc get from List with function_ids, i
        proc add from Set with pure_functions, function_id
        proc add from Set with const_functions, function_id
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Analyze each function for purity
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Set function_id to proc get from List with function_ids, i
        Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id

        analyze_function_purity(wpa, ipa_info)

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Propagate purity information through call graph
    propagate_purity_information(wpa)

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
analyze_function_purity checks if a function is pure.
Updates is_pure and is_const fields based on side effect analysis.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_function_purity" that takes wpa as Integer, ipa_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Let side_effect_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88
    Let pure_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 72
    Let const_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 80
    Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 0

    Note: Check side effect flags
    Let has_writes be side_effect_flags bitwise_and SIDE_EFFECT_MEMORY_WRITE
    Let has_io be side_effect_flags bitwise_and SIDE_EFFECT_IO
    Let has_exceptions be side_effect_flags bitwise_and SIDE_EFFECT_EXCEPTION
    Let has_external be side_effect_flags bitwise_and SIDE_EFFECT_EXTERNAL_CALL
    Let has_global be side_effect_flags bitwise_and SIDE_EFFECT_GLOBAL_STATE

    Note: Function is pure if no side effects at all
    If has_writes is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 72, 0 Note: not pure
        proc remove from Set with pure_functions, function_id
    End If

    If has_io is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 72, 0
        proc remove from Set with pure_functions, function_id
    End If

    If has_exceptions is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 72, 0
        proc remove from Set with pure_functions, function_id
    End If

    If has_external is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 72, 0
        proc remove from Set with pure_functions, function_id
    End If

    Note: Function is const if no global state mutation
    If has_global is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 80, 0 Note: not const
        proc remove from Set with const_functions, function_id
    End If

    If has_writes is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 80, 0
        proc remove from Set with const_functions, function_id
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_call_side_effects propagates side effects through call graph.
If function A calls function B, A inherits B's side effects.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_call_side_effects" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64

    Note: Get all functions
    Let function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with side_effect_info
    Let function_count be proc length from List with function_ids

    Note: Propagate side effects through call graph
    Note: If function A calls function B, A inherits B's side effects
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let function_id be proc get from List with function_ids, i
        Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id

        Note: Get callees from call graph
        Let callees be proc get_function_callees from CallGraph with call_graph, function_id
        Let callee_count be proc length from List with callees

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than callee_count:
            Let call_site be proc get from List with callees, j
            Let callee_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 8

            If callee_id is not equal to 0:
                Note: Get callee's side effects
                Let callee_ipa be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, callee_id
                If callee_ipa is not equal to 0:
                    Let callee_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_ipa, 88

                    Note: Inherit callee's side effects
                    Let caller_flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88
                    Let combined_flags be caller_flags bitwise_or callee_flags
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 88, combined_flags
                End If
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
propagate_purity_information propagates purity through call graph.
If function A calls impure function B, A is also impure.
Requires fixed-point iteration until no changes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "propagate_purity_information" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64
    Let pure_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 72

    Note: Fixed-point iteration
    Let changed be 1
    While changed is equal to 1:
        Set changed to 0

        Note: For each function, check if it calls impure functions
        Let function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with side_effect_info
        Let function_count be proc length from List with function_ids

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than function_count:
            Let function_id be proc get from List with function_ids, i

            Note: Check if currently marked as pure
            Let is_pure be proc contains from Set with pure_functions, function_id
            If is_pure is equal to 1:
                Note: Check all callees
                Let callees be proc get_function_callees from CallGraph with call_graph, function_id
                Let callee_count be proc length from List with callees

                Let j be 0
                While j is less than callee_count:
                    Let call_site be proc get from List with callees, j
                    Let callee_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 8

                    If callee_id is not equal to 0:
                        Note: Check if callee is pure
                        Let callee_pure be proc contains from Set with pure_functions, callee_id
                        If callee_pure is equal to 0:
                            Note: Callee is impure, so caller is impure
                            proc remove from Set with pure_functions, function_id

                            Note: Update IPA info
                            Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 72, 0

                            Set changed to 1
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_const_functions identifies const functions (no global state mutation).
Const functions can read globals but not write them.
Similar to pure functions but allows local memory writes.
@End Reasoning

Process called "identify_const_functions" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64
    Let const_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 80

    Note: Const functions already initialized in compute_pure_functions
    Note: analyze_function_purity already updated is_const flags
    Note: Just need to propagate through call graph

    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8

    Note: Fixed-point iteration for const propagation
    Let changed be 1
    While changed is equal to 1:
        Set changed to 0

        Let function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with side_effect_info
        Let function_count be proc length from List with function_ids

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than function_count:
            Let function_id be proc get from List with function_ids, i

            Let is_const be proc contains from Set with const_functions, function_id
            If is_const is equal to 1:
                Note: Check all callees
                Let callees be proc get_function_callees from CallGraph with call_graph, function_id
                Let callee_count be proc length from List with callees

                Let j be 0
                While j is less than callee_count:
                    Let call_site be proc get from List with callees, j
                    Let callee_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, 8

                    If callee_id is not equal to 0:
                        Let callee_const be proc contains from Set with const_functions, callee_id
                        If callee_const is equal to 0:
                            Note: Callee is not const, so caller is not const
                            proc remove from Set with const_functions, function_id

                            Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id
                            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 80, 0

                            Set changed to 1
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Phase 5: Global Visibility Analysis
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
compute_global_visibility determines which functions/globals are visible outside module.
Visibility affects what can be optimized (hidden symbols can be more aggressively optimized).

Visibility categories:
- Exported: Explicitly exported from module
- Address-taken: Address stored in variable or passed as function pointer
- Internal: Only called directly, never exported or address-taken
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_global_visibility" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0

    Note: Phase 1: Mark exported functions (already done in identify_entry_points)

    Note: Phase 2: Mark address-taken functions
    mark_address_taken_functions(wpa, mir)

    Note: Phase 3: Propagate visibility through call graph
    propagate_visibility(wpa)

    Note: Phase 4: Identify internal functions
    identify_internal_functions(wpa)

    Note: Phase 5: Compute dead code
    compute_dead_code(wpa)

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
mark_exported_functions marks functions that are exported from module.
Exported functions cannot be eliminated or renamed.
@End Reasoning

Process called "mark_exported_functions" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88

    Note: Get all functions
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0

        Note: Check metadata for export flag
        Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 88
        If metadata is not equal to 0:
            Let flags be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with metadata, 8
            Let is_exported be flags bitwise_and 1
            If is_exported is equal to 1:
                proc add from Set with exported_functions, function_id
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
mark_address_taken_functions marks functions whose address is taken.
Address-taken functions cannot be eliminated and must retain their symbols.

A function's address is taken if:
- ADDRESS_OF instruction targets the function
- Function is stored in a variable or data structure
- Function is passed as callback to another function
@End Reasoning

Process called "mark_address_taken_functions" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let address_taken be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96

    Note: Get all functions
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Note: Scan all functions for ADDRESS_OF operations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8

        If cfg is not equal to 0:
            Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
            Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

            Let b be 0
            While b is less than block_count:
                Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
                Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

                Let j be 0
                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

                    Note: Check for ADDRESS_OF (20205)
                    If opcode is equal to 20205:
                        Let target_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16

                        Note: Use type analysis to determine if target is function
                        Let entity_type be get_entity_type(mir, target_value)

                        Note: Entity type 1 = function, 2 = variable
                        If entity_type is equal to 1:
                            Note: Target is a function - mark as address-taken
                            proc add from Set with address_taken, target_value
                        End If
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While

                Set b to b plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
propagate_visibility propagates visibility constraints through call graph.
If function A calls address-taken function B, A must also be visible.
@End Reasoning

Process called "propagate_visibility" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88
    Let address_taken be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96

    Note: Visibility already captured by exported and address-taken sets
    Note: No further propagation needed for basic visibility

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_internal_functions identifies functions that are completely internal.
Internal functions are not exported and not address-taken.
These can be most aggressively optimized (inlined, eliminated, renamed).
@End Reasoning

Process called "identify_internal_functions" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88
    Let address_taken be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96

    Note: Get all functions
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Note: Internal functions are those not exported and not address-taken
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0

        Let is_exported be proc contains from Set with exported_functions, function_id
        Let is_address_taken be proc contains from Set with address_taken, function_id

        If is_exported is equal to 0:
            If is_address_taken is equal to 0:
                Note: This is an internal function
                Note: Can be marked for aggressive optimization
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_dead_code identifies dead code at whole-program level.
Dead code includes unreachable functions and unused globals.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_dead_code" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find unreachable functions
    find_unreachable_functions(wpa)

    Note: Find unused globals
    find_unused_globals(wpa)

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
find_unreachable_functions performs the post-reachability extraction
and verification pass. After E3-hardened compute_global_reachability
has run, reachable_functions is the sound transitive closure over
direct, indirect, virtual, address-taken, and exported edges. This
Process iterates every function ID known to the call graph and stamps
the complement into unreachable_functions, then verifies the two
post-condition predicates that are cheap to check (P-EXP and P-AT):

  P-EXP: exported_functions is a subset of reachable_functions
  P-AT:  address_taken_functions is a subset of reachable_functions

On predicate violation the Process emits a diagnostic and returns -1;
the LTO orchestrator interprets a negative return as "skip DCE for
this build" (fail-safe — over-eager DCE could delete code that some
external entry actually calls).

On success the Process returns the count of unreachable functions,
which the caller uses as the DCE plan input.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Clear any prior contents of unreachable_functions (idempotent).
2. Walk call_graph.nodes keys; for each ID not in reachable, add to
   unreachable.
3. Verify P-EXP by walking exported_functions and asserting each is
   in reachable.
4. Verify P-AT similarly for address_taken_functions.
5. Return Set.size(unreachable) on success or -1 on predicate
   violation.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|functions| + |exported| + |address_taken|). Each Set.contains is
O(1) amortized; the worklist walk in step 2 is O(|functions|).
Verification (steps 3-4) adds O(|exported| + |address_taken|) which
is typically a small fraction of the total. The whole pass completes
in microseconds for typical programs.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Soundness gate for whole-program DCE. A bug in compute_global_reachability
that omits an exported function would normally manifest as deleted code
in the final binary. The P-EXP / P-AT verification catches this class
of regression at WPA build time rather than at runtime; the -1 return
forces the orchestrator to suppress DCE rather than ship a corrupted
binary.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "find_unreachable_functions" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Let reachable_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    Let unreachable_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 32
    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88
    Let address_taken_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96

    If call_graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1 — clear any prior contents of unreachable_functions for idempotency.
    clear_set(unreachable_functions)

    Note: Step 2 — walk call graph nodes and stamp the complement.
    Let cg_nodes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_graph, 0
    Let all_function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with cg_nodes
    Let all_count be proc length from List with all_function_ids

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than all_count:
        Let function_id be proc get from List with all_function_ids, i
        Let is_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable_functions, function_id
        If is_reachable is equal to 0:
            proc add from Set with unreachable_functions, function_id
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 3 — verify P-EXP (exported ⊆ reachable).
    If exported_functions is not equal to 0:
        Let exp_list be proc to_list from Set with exported_functions
        Let exp_count be proc length from List with exp_list
        Let e be 0
        While e is less than exp_count:
            Let exp_id be proc get from List with exp_list, e
            Let exp_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable_functions, exp_id
            If exp_reachable is equal to 0:
                Alert "[WPA SOUNDNESS] find_unreachable_functions: P-EXP violation — exported function not in reachable set"
                Return 0 minus 1
            End If
            Set e to e plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Step 4 — verify P-AT (address_taken ⊆ reachable).
    If address_taken_functions is not equal to 0:
        Let at_list be proc to_list from Set with address_taken_functions
        Let at_count be proc length from List with at_list
        Let a be 0
        While a is less than at_count:
            Let at_id be proc get from List with at_list, a
            Let at_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable_functions, at_id
            If at_reachable is equal to 0:
                Alert "[WPA SOUNDNESS] find_unreachable_functions: P-AT violation — address-taken function not in reachable set"
                Return 0 minus 1
            End If
            Set a to a plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Step 5 — return count of unreachable functions for the DCE plan caller.
    Let unreachable_count be proc size from Set with unreachable_functions
    Return unreachable_count
End Process

@Reasoning
find_unused_globals finds global variables that are never accessed.
Unused globals are dead code and can be eliminated.
@End Reasoning

Process called "find_unused_globals" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let constant_globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 120

    Note: Get all globals from MIR
    Let globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 16
    Let global_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 24

    Note: Build set of accessed globals by scanning all function bodies
    Let accessed_globals be proc create from Set

    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8

        If cfg is not equal to 0:
            Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
            Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

            Let b be 0
            While b is less than block_count:
                Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
                Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

                Let j be 0
                While j is less than inst_count:
                    Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, j
                    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

                    Note: Check for global access instructions
                    Note: LOAD and STORE to global addresses
                    If opcode is equal to 20200:
                        Let address be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                        proc add from Set with accessed_globals, address
                    End If

                    If opcode is equal to 20201:
                        Set address to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                        proc add from Set with accessed_globals, address
                    End If

                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While

                Set b to b plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Globals not in accessed_globals set are unused

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Phase 6: Optimization Opportunities
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
identify_cross_module_inlining identifies cross-module inlining opportunities.
Uses whole-program call graph to find profitable inlining across module boundaries.
@End Reasoning

Process called "identify_cross_module_inlining" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Let inlining_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 112

    Note: Use call graph's identify_inlining_candidates
    Let candidates be proc identify_inlining_candidates from CallGraph with call_graph, Layout.memory_get_int64(wpa, 0 , 50)

    Note: Filter to cross-module calls only using module information from MIR
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let module_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 32 Note: Function ID → Module ID map

    Let candidate_count be proc length from List with candidates
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than candidate_count:
        Let candidate be proc get from List with candidates, i

        Note: Extract caller and callee from candidate
        Let caller_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 0
        Let callee_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 8

        Note: Get module IDs for both functions
        Let caller_module be proc get from Dictionary with module_map, caller_id
        Let callee_module be proc get from Dictionary with module_map, callee_id

        Note: Only include if cross-module (different modules)
        If caller_module is not equal to callee_module:
            proc append from List with inlining_candidates, candidate
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_inlining_benefit computes cost-benefit score for inlining.
Considers: size increase, call frequency, optimization opportunities enabled.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_inlining_benefit" that takes wpa as Integer, caller_id as Integer, callee_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8

    Note: Get callee function
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Let callee_size be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0

        If function_id is equal to callee_id:
            Note: Count instructions in function
            Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
            If cfg is not equal to 0:
                Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
                Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

                Let b be 0
                While b is less than block_count:
                    Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                    Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
                    Set callee_size to callee_size plus inst_count
                    Set b to b plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute comprehensive cost-benefit score
    Note: Benefit = call_frequency * optimization_value - size_cost

    Note: Get call frequency from call graph
    Let call_freq be get_call_frequency(call_graph, caller_id, callee_id)

    Note: Estimate optimization opportunities enabled by inlining
    Let opt_value be estimate_optimization_potential(mir, caller_id, callee_id)

    Note: Calculate size cost (penalize large functions)
    Let size_cost be callee_size multiplied by 2  Note: Each instruction costs 2 points

    Note: Bonus for leaf functions (no further inlining complexity)
    Let is_leaf be is_leaf_function(mir, callee_id)
    Let leaf_bonus be 0
    If is_leaf is equal to 1:
        Set leaf_bonus to 50  Note: Leaf functions are cheaper to inline
    End If

    Note: Bonus for eliminating call overhead
    Let call_overhead_saving be 10

    Note: Final benefit calculation
    Let benefit be (call_freq multiplied by opt_value) plus call_overhead_saving plus leaf_bonus minus size_cost

    Return benefit
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper functions for inline benefit calculation.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_call_frequency" that takes call_graph as Integer, caller_id as Integer, callee_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get edge info from call graph
    Let edges be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_graph, 8
    Let edge_key be (caller_id multiplied by 1000000) plus callee_id
    Let edge_info be proc get from Dictionary with edges, edge_key

    If edge_info is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Default frequency
    End If

    Note: Extract frequency from edge info
    Let freq be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with edge_info, 8
    Return freq
End Process

Process called "estimate_optimization_potential" that takes mir as Integer, caller_id as Integer, callee_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Estimate how much optimization opportunity inlining creates
    Note: Factors: constant propagation, dead code elimination, specialization

    Let base_value be 20  Note: Base optimization value

    Note: Check if callee has parameters that could be constant-folded
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let callee_func be proc get from Dictionary with functions, callee_id

    If callee_func is not equal to 0:
        Let param_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_func, 40

        Note: Each parameter is potential constant propagation opportunity
        Set base_value to base_value plus (param_count multiplied by 5)

        Note: Check for loops (unrolling potential)
        Let has_loops be function_has_loops(callee_func)
        If has_loops is equal to 1:
            Set base_value to base_value plus 15
        End If
    End If

    Return base_value
End Process

Process called "is_leaf_function" that takes mir as Integer, func_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if function makes no calls (leaf function)
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let func be proc get from Dictionary with functions, func_id

    If func is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: No CFG means no calls
    End If

    Note: Scan all blocks for CALL instructions
    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

            Note: Check for CALL (20304) or CALL_INDIRECT (20305)
            If opcode is equal to 20304:
                Return 0  Note: Found call, not a leaf
            End If
            If opcode is equal to 20305:
                Return 0  Note: Found indirect call, not a leaf
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 1  Note: No calls found, is leaf
End Process

Process called "function_has_loops" that takes func as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Simple loop detection: check for back edges in CFG
    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let successors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 8

        If successors is not equal to 0:
            Let succ_count be proc length from List with successors

            Let s be 0
            While s is less than succ_count:
                Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, s

                Note: Back edge if successor ID <= current block ID
                If succ_id is less than or equal to b:
                    Return 1  Note: Found back edge, has loop
                End If

                Set s to s plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 0  Note: No loops found
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_constant_propagation finds global constants for propagation.
Constants that are never modified can be propagated throughout program.

The P1-E v3 expansion of this Process beyond its original single-line
identify_global_constants wrapper is to materialise a CPCandidate
record (24 bytes) per surviving constant global so that
compute_optimization_priorities can rank the bucket-0x0007 entries
against every other category (inlining, devirt, DCE, specialization).
Without this expansion the cross-bucket priority scheduler is blind
to CP work and routinely starves it behind cheaper-but-less-valuable
inlining wins.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Defensive null guard: wpa of 0 returns 0.
2. Load mir from wpa[0], constant_globals (Set) from wpa[120], and
   cp_candidates (List) from wpa[152].
3. Run identify_global_constants(wpa, mir) — populates constant_globals
   by optimistic-initialise-then-prune: every global is initially
   marked constant; any global written by any function (per the
   side_effect_info Dictionary at wpa[64]) is then removed.
4. Defensive-allocate cp_candidates if the WPA struct was constructed
   bypassing create_whole_program_analysis.
5. Walk constant_globals as a List via Set.to_list and, for each
   surviving global_id, build a CPCandidate via allocate_cp_candidate
   (which counts the LOAD use_count across reachable functions and
   records the value_size_est for the priority scorer).
6. Append every non-null CPCandidate to cp_candidates.
7. Return the candidate count so the orchestrator can log progress.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two passes:
  - identify_global_constants: O(|globals| + |functions| * |writes|).
  - CPCandidate construction: O(|constants| * |reachable_functions| *
    |instructions_per_function|) inside allocate_cp_candidate's LOAD-
    count walk.

For a 10k-function program with a few hundred constant globals each
referenced in <100 functions, the total cost is single-digit
milliseconds. The dominant factor is allocate_cp_candidate's
function-by-function LOAD scan, not the constant-globals identification.
The Process is called once per compile job (Phase 8a) so the cost is
amortised across the full LTO budget.

Memory: one 24-byte CPCandidate per surviving constant global. For
a generous 1000-constant program that totals 24 KB of long-lived
allocation, freed by destroy_whole_program_analysis at tear-down.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. No untrusted input. The Process consumes already-
parsed MIR plus the WPA-owned side_effect_info / constant_globals
collections.

Soundness invariant: a global classified as constant MUST NOT be
written by any reachable function. identify_global_constants enforces
this by ANDing the constant set against memory_writes from every
function's InterProceduralInfo record. A bug in side_effect_info
population could under-report writes and produce an unsafe constant
classification, but that is the responsibility of compute_side_effects
(Phase 6), not of this Process. apply_constant_propagation in CMO
re-validates each candidate against MIR before committing the
replacement, providing a second line of defense.

Allocation failure inside allocate_cp_candidate returns 0 from the
constructor; this Process silently skips such entries (degraded
coverage, not miscompilation).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "identify_constant_propagation" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let constant_globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 120
    Let cp_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 152

    Note: Populate constant_globals.
    identify_global_constants(wpa, mir)

    Note: Walk constant_globals and build a CPCandidate record for each.
    Note: This is what feeds bucket 0x0007 in compute_optimization_priorities.
    If cp_candidates is equal to 0:
        Note: Defensive: allocate if create_whole_program_analysis was bypassed.
        Set cp_candidates to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 152, cp_candidates
    End If

    If constant_globals is not equal to 0:
        Let globals_list be proc to_list from Set with constant_globals
        Let gc be proc length from List with globals_list

        Let g be 0
        While g is less than gc:
            Let global_id be proc get from List with globals_list, g
            Let cp_record be allocate_cp_candidate(global_id, mir, wpa)
            If cp_record is not equal to 0:
                proc append from List with cp_candidates, cp_record
            End If
            Set g to g plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let cp_count be proc length from List with cp_candidates
    Return cp_count
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_global_constants finds global variables that are compile-time constants.
Constants are never written after initialization.
@End Reasoning

Process called "identify_global_constants" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let constant_globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 120
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64

    Note: Get all globals
    Let globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 16
    Let global_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 24

    Note: Optimistic initialization: add all globals, then remove non-constants
    Note: Globals written to will be removed in scanning phase
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than global_count:
        Let global_var be proc get from List with globals, i
        Let global_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with global_var, 0
        proc add from Set with constant_globals, global_id
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Scan all functions for writes to globals
    Let function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with side_effect_info
    Let function_count be proc length from List with function_ids

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let function_id be proc get from List with function_ids, i
        Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id

        Note: Get memory writes
        Let memory_writes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 32
        Let write_count be proc size from Set with memory_writes

        Note: For each write, remove from constant set
        Let writes_list be proc to_list from Set with memory_writes
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than write_count:
            Let written_global be proc get from List with writes_list, j
            proc remove from Set with constant_globals, written_global
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_function_specialization finds functions that can be specialized.
Specialization creates optimized versions for specific argument values.

The P1-E v3 expansion materialises a SpecCandidate record (32 bytes)
per qualifying function so that compute_optimization_priorities can
rank specialization opportunities into bucket 0x0008 alongside the
other optimization categories. The original implementation computed
the benefit score and discarded it; this version captures the score
plus the dominant-constant-argument index, which apply_specialization
in CMO consumes to drive the clone's constant-fold pipeline.

Candidate qualification is the conjunction of:
  - caller_count > 2  (multiple callers — single-caller specialization
    is just inlining and is handled by the inlining bucket).
  - compute_specialization_benefit > SPECIALIZATION_BENEFIT_FLOOR
    (typically 50; below this the clone cost is unlikely to be
    recovered).

find_dominant_constant_arg is queried per candidate to record the
parameter index that is most often constant across call sites; the
specialization apply pass uses this index as the constant-fold seed
when generating the clone. A return of -1 (no dominant index) is
preserved as-is and apply_specialization falls back to its
generic-clone path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Defensive null guard: wpa of 0 returns 0.
2. Load call_graph (wpa[8]), mir (wpa[0]), and spec_candidates list
   (wpa[160]). Defensive-allocate spec_candidates if the WPA struct
   was constructed bypassing create_whole_program_analysis. Bail out
   with 0 if call_graph is null (no graph -> no candidates).
3. Walk cg_nodes (the CallGraph's function-id-keyed Dictionary at
   offset 0). For each CallGraphNode read caller_count at offset 40.
4. For nodes with caller_count > 2:
     a. compute_specialization_benefit(wpa, function_id) returns a
        raw score (instruction count divided by 10, see helper).
     b. If benefit > SPECIALIZATION_BENEFIT_FLOOR:
        - find_dominant_constant_arg(wpa, function_id) yields the
          parameter index (or -1).
        - allocate_spec_candidate builds the 32-byte record.
        - Append to spec_candidates if non-null.
5. Return the candidate count.

The two helper queries (compute_specialization_benefit and
find_dominant_constant_arg) are encapsulated rather than inlined to
keep this Process as a pure orchestrator and to allow swap-in of
more sophisticated heuristics without touching the orchestration
shape.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|functions| * (benefit_cost + dominant_arg_cost)).
  - benefit_cost in compute_specialization_benefit walks the MIR
    function's CFG once (per-function O(|instructions|)).
  - dominant_arg_cost in find_dominant_constant_arg walks the
    function's callers and reads constant-ness for each call site's
    arguments (O(|callers| * |params|)).

The outer loop runs once per function in the call graph; the inner
helper queries skip non-candidate functions in O(1) (the
caller_count > 2 gate). For a 10k-function program the total cost is
single-digit milliseconds, dominated by compute_specialization_benefit
on the candidates that pass the caller-count gate (typically <5% of
all functions).

Memory: one 32-byte SpecCandidate per qualifying function. For a
generous candidate density (~200 candidates in a 10k-function build)
that totals 6.4 KB of long-lived allocation, released by
destroy_whole_program_analysis at tear-down.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. No untrusted input. Operates on the WPA call
graph plus MIR.

Soundness invariant: a SpecCandidate must reference a function_id
that exists in MIR with a body the specialization apply pass can
clone. The walk uses cg_nodes keys (each of which is a function ID
the call_graph builder verified against MIR during Phase 1), so
mis-referenced IDs are impossible by construction.

An over-aggressive candidate set (false positives — clones that
don't pay for themselves) wastes code size but does not miscompile;
apply_specialization in CMO re-checks the benefit at clone time and
discards non-profitable candidates before committing. An
under-aggressive set (false negatives — missed clones) merely loses
optimization opportunity. The Process therefore biases toward
recording, with the floor and caller-count gate the only filtering.

allocate_spec_candidate returns 0 on allocation failure; this
Process silently skips such entries (degraded coverage, not
miscompilation).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "identify_function_specialization" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let spec_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 160

    If spec_candidates is equal to 0:
        Note: Defensive: allocate if create_whole_program_analysis was bypassed.
        Set spec_candidates to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 160, spec_candidates
    End If

    If call_graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Scan call graph for frequently called functions with constant arguments.
    Let cg_nodes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_graph, 0
    Let function_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with cg_nodes
    Let function_count be proc length from List with function_ids

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let function_id be proc get from List with function_ids, i
        Let node be proc get from Dictionary with cg_nodes, function_id

        Note: Read caller_count at offset 40 of CallGraphNode.
        Let caller_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40

        If caller_count is greater than 2:
            Note: Multiple callers — check for specialization opportunity.
            Let benefit be compute_specialization_benefit(wpa, function_id)
            If benefit is greater than SPECIALIZATION_BENEFIT_FLOOR:
                Note: Record the candidate so compute_optimization_priorities can
                Note: rank it into bucket 0x0008.
                Let dominant_arg be find_dominant_constant_arg(wpa, function_id)
                Let sp_record be allocate_spec_candidate(function_id, caller_count, benefit, dominant_arg)
                If sp_record is not equal to 0:
                    proc append from List with spec_candidates, sp_record
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let sp_count be proc length from List with spec_candidates
    Return sp_count
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_specialization_benefit computes benefit of specializing a function.
Higher benefit when function has expensive computations on constant arguments.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_specialization_benefit" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0

    Note: Get function from MIR
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Let benefit be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        Let fid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0

        If fid is equal to function_id:
            Note: Count parameter-dependent operations
            Note: More parameter usage = higher specialization benefit
            Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
            If cfg is not equal to 0:
                Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
                Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

                Let b be 0
                While b is less than block_count:
                    Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                    Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
                    Set benefit to benefit plus inst_count
                    Set b to b plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Simple heuristic: benefit = instruction count / 10
    Set benefit to benefit divided by 10

    Return benefit
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_whole_program_dce builds the aggregate DCEPlan that the CMO
sweep passes consume. It depends on find_unreachable_functions having
populated wpa.unreachable_functions and on identify_virtual_call_elimination
having filtered the devirt candidates (a filtered devirt candidate may
keep a function alive by directing an indirect call to it).

The plan combines three dead categories:
  - dead functions: from unreachable_functions
  - dead globals: globals whose only readers are dead functions
  - dead types: types referenced only inside dead functions
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Run find_unreachable_functions to ensure the soundness pass has
   completed (idempotent; no-op if already run).
2. Allocate a 40-byte DCEPlan struct.
3. Extract a stable, sorted List of dead functions via
   sorted_list_from_set (deterministic iteration order matters for
   reproducible byte-identical builds).
4. Compute the dead-globals list using compute_reachable_filtered_dead_globals.
5. Compute the dead-types list using compute_dead_types.
6. Store the plan pointer at wpa[128].
7. Return total dead count = dead_funcs + dead_globals + dead_types.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
The dominant cost is compute_reachable_filtered_dead_globals (one
MIR walk to identify global accesses by dead functions) and
compute_dead_types (one walk over types intersected with the dead
function set). Both are O(|MIR|) one-shot passes. The DCEPlan
allocation is a single 40-byte block; the contained Lists are
allocated once each and never resized after this Process completes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The plan is consumed by CMO's sweep_dead_functions / sweep_dead_globals.
Over-aggressive DCE deletes used code (binary corruption). The
soundness guard is in find_unreachable_functions (the predicate check)
plus identify_virtual_call_elimination (the devirt filter that keeps
indirect targets alive). This Process trusts the inputs and aggregates;
no additional soundness check is performed here.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "identify_whole_program_dce" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let unreachable_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 32

    Note: Step 1 — ensure the reachability extraction has run. The Process is
    Note: idempotent because find_unreachable_functions starts with a clear_set
    Note: of the unreachable_functions Set.
    Let extract_result be find_unreachable_functions(wpa)
    If extract_result is less than 0:
        Note: P-EXP / P-AT violation — refuse to build a DCE plan, so the
        Note: orchestrator skips DCE for this build (fail-safe).
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2 — allocate DCEPlan (40 bytes).
    Let dce_plan be proc allocate from Layout with DCE_PLAN_SIZE
    If dce_plan is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 3 — dead functions, sorted for determinism.
    Let dead_funcs be sorted_list_from_set(unreachable_functions)
    Let dead_func_count be proc length from List with dead_funcs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 0, dead_funcs
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 8, dead_func_count

    Note: Step 4 — dead globals.
    Let dead_globals be compute_reachable_filtered_dead_globals(wpa)
    Let dead_global_count be 0
    If dead_globals is not equal to 0:
        Set dead_global_count to proc length from List with dead_globals
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 16, dead_globals
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 24, dead_global_count

    Note: Step 5 — dead types.
    Let dead_types be compute_dead_types(wpa, dead_funcs)
    Let dead_type_count be 0
    If dead_types is not equal to 0:
        Set dead_type_count to proc length from List with dead_types
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 32, dead_types

    Note: Step 6 — store the plan pointer on the WPA struct.
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 128, dce_plan

    Note: Step 7 — return aggregate dead count.
    Return dead_func_count plus dead_global_count plus dead_type_count
End Process

@Reasoning
identify_virtual_call_elimination filters, normalizes, and elevates
the raw devirtualization candidates produced by
compute_devirtualization_candidates. Filtering rules:

  - drop any candidate whose target is in unreachable_functions
  - drop any candidate whose call site has no containing function
    in the MIR (the instruction has already been deleted by some
    earlier pass)
  - drop any candidate whose containing function is not in
    reachable_functions (the call site itself is dead)
  - drop any candidate whose target is not a method registered in
    the type hierarchy (defense — should never trigger but cheap)

Survivors get their verified flag (offset 24) set to 1; the
is_speculative bit (offset 32) is already populated by the producer.
The wpa.devirtualization_candidates list is replaced with the
filtered list. Returns exact + speculative count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Snapshot the raw list, run normalize_devirt_candidates as a
   defense-in-depth pass against any legacy shape leaking through.
2. Build the inst -> function index once via build_inst_to_function_index.
3. Iterate normalized candidates, applying the four filters.
4. Replace wpa.devirtualization_candidates with the filtered List.
5. Return verified candidate count.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
The inst -> function index is O(|MIR|) one-time cost. Per-candidate
filtering is O(1) using the index plus Set membership tests.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
A speculative devirtualization that survives this filter and is
applied without a guarded runtime check would cause dispatch-to-wrong-
callee. CMO's apply_devirtualization for confidence=0 candidates
inserts the runtime guard, so the filter's job here is correctness
of the candidate set, not of the guard. Soundness of the verified
flag depends on the upstream type-hierarchy being well-formed; a
malformed hierarchy is a frontend bug not reachable from here.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "identify_virtual_call_elimination" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let raw_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104
    Let unreachable_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 32
    Let reachable_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0

    Note: Step 1 — normalize (defense-in-depth; production path is no-op).
    Let normalized be normalize_devirt_candidates(raw_candidates)
    If normalized is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2 — build inst -> function index.
    Let inst_to_func be build_inst_to_function_index(mir)

    Note: Step 3 — filter pass.
    Let filtered be proc create from List
    Let exact_count be 0
    Let speculative_count be 0

    Let candidate_count be proc length from List with normalized
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than candidate_count:
        Let candidate be proc get from List with normalized, i

        Let call_site be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 0
        Let target be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 8
        Let confidence be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 16

        Let keep be 1

        Note: Filter 1 — target must not be dead.
        Let target_unreachable be proc contains from Set with unreachable_functions, target
        If target_unreachable is equal to 1:
            Set keep to 0
        End If

        Note: Filter 2 — call site must still have a containing function.
        Let containing_func be 0
        If keep is equal to 1:
            If inst_to_func is not equal to 0:
                Set containing_func to proc get from Dictionary with inst_to_func, call_site
            End If
            If containing_func is equal to 0:
                Set keep to 0
            End If
        End If

        Note: Filter 3 — containing function must be reachable.
        If keep is equal to 1:
            Let cont_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable_functions, containing_func
            If cont_reachable is equal to 0:
                Set keep to 0
            End If
        End If

        Note: Filter 4 — target must be a method in the type hierarchy.
        If keep is equal to 1:
            Let in_hierarchy be is_method_in_hierarchy(type_hierarchy, target)
            If in_hierarchy is equal to 0:
                Set keep to 0
            End If
        End If

        If keep is equal to 1:
            Note: Stamp verified=1 and elevate into filtered list.
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with candidate, 24, 1
            proc append from List with filtered, candidate

            If confidence is equal to 1:
                Set exact_count to exact_count plus 1
            End If
            If confidence is equal to 0:
                Set speculative_count to speculative_count plus 1
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Step 4 — replace WPA's candidate list with the filtered one.
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104, filtered

    Note: Step 5 — return total verified count.
    Return exact_count plus speculative_count
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_optimization_priorities builds a cross-bucket priority Dict
keyed by composite bucket-tagged optimization IDs. The Dict layout:

  key   = (bucket_tag << 48) | index_in_bucket
  value = priority_score (Integer)

Eight buckets cover the full LTO opportunity space (inlining, exact
devirt, speculative devirt, DCE-func, DCE-global, DCE-type, CP, spec).
The priority-driven CMO path at O3 reads this Dict, sorts it by score
descending, and applies opportunities in priority order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Fetch the Dict at wpa[136] (allocated by create_whole_program_analysis).
2. For each bucket, iterate the corresponding candidate list and:
   - compute score via the bucket-specific score_* helper
   - compose the composite key
   - insert (key, score) into the Dict
3. Return Dict.size (total candidates ranked).

The DCE buckets need three sub-passes: one over dead_funcs (bucket
0x0004), one over dead_globals (0x0005), one over dead_types (0x0006).
Each entry's score includes a size_reduction_bonus that is unique to
the DCE buckets (no other bucket's score formula references it).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Linear in total candidate count. For a 10k-function program the
total candidate count is typically a few hundred; the Dict
construction completes in sub-millisecond. The downstream
priority-driven CMO sorts this Dict once per compile (O(n log n)
on n candidates).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Mis-ranking degrades codegen quality but does not affect correctness;
out-of-order application of optimizations is safe by construction
(each apply_* in CMO is independently sound). No untrusted data;
all scoring inputs come from the WPA struct.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_optimization_priorities" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let priorities be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 136
    If priorities is equal to 0:
        Note: Fallback — allocate if it was never created (defensive).
        Set priorities to proc create from Dictionary
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 136, priorities
    End If

    Let inlining_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 112
    Let devirt_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104
    Let dce_plan be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 128
    Let cp_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 152
    Let spec_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 160

    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Bucket 0x0001 — inlining
    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    If inlining_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let inl_count be proc length from List with inlining_candidates
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inl_count:
            Let cand be proc get from List with inlining_candidates, i
            Let score be score_inlining(cand, wpa)
            Let key be (BUCKET_TAG_INLINING multiplied by BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT) plus i
            proc set from Dictionary with priorities, key, score
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Buckets 0x0002 / 0x0003 — devirt (exact vs speculative)
    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    If devirt_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let dv_count be proc length from List with devirt_candidates
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than dv_count:
            Let dvc be proc get from List with devirt_candidates, j
            Let dv_score be score_devirt(dvc, wpa)
            Let is_spec be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dvc, 32
            Let dv_bucket be BUCKET_TAG_DEVIRT_EXACT
            If is_spec is equal to 1:
                Set dv_bucket to BUCKET_TAG_DEVIRT_SPEC
            End If
            Let dv_key be (dv_bucket multiplied by BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT) plus j
            proc set from Dictionary with priorities, dv_key, dv_score
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Bucket 0x0004 — DCE dead functions
    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    If dce_plan is not equal to 0:
        Let dead_funcs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 0
        Let dead_func_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 8
        If dead_funcs is not equal to 0:
            Let k be 0
            While k is less than dead_func_count:
                Let df_score be score_dce(dce_plan, BUCKET_TAG_DCE_FUNC, k, wpa)
                Let df_key be (BUCKET_TAG_DCE_FUNC multiplied by BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT) plus k
                proc set from Dictionary with priorities, df_key, df_score
                Set k to k plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Note: --------------------------------------------------------
        Note: Bucket 0x0005 — DCE dead globals
        Note: --------------------------------------------------------
        Let dead_globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 16
        Let dead_global_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 24
        If dead_globals is not equal to 0:
            Let g be 0
            While g is less than dead_global_count:
                Let dg_score be score_dce(dce_plan, BUCKET_TAG_DCE_GLOBAL, g, wpa)
                Let dg_key be (BUCKET_TAG_DCE_GLOBAL multiplied by BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT) plus g
                proc set from Dictionary with priorities, dg_key, dg_score
                Set g to g plus 1
            End While
        End If

        Note: --------------------------------------------------------
        Note: Bucket 0x0006 — DCE dead types
        Note: --------------------------------------------------------
        Let dead_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 32
        If dead_types is not equal to 0:
            Let dt_count be proc length from List with dead_types
            Let t be 0
            While t is less than dt_count:
                Let dt_score be score_dce(dce_plan, BUCKET_TAG_DCE_TYPE, t, wpa)
                Let dt_key be (BUCKET_TAG_DCE_TYPE multiplied by BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT) plus t
                proc set from Dictionary with priorities, dt_key, dt_score
                Set t to t plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Bucket 0x0007 — constant propagation
    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    If cp_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let cp_count be proc length from List with cp_candidates
        Let c be 0
        While c is less than cp_count:
            Let cpc be proc get from List with cp_candidates, c
            Let cp_global_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cpc, 0
            Let cp_score be score_constant_prop(cp_global_id, wpa)
            Let cp_key be (BUCKET_TAG_CP multiplied by BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT) plus c
            proc set from Dictionary with priorities, cp_key, cp_score
            Set c to c plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    Note: Bucket 0x0008 — specialization
    Note: ------------------------------------------------------------
    If spec_candidates is not equal to 0:
        Let sp_count be proc length from List with spec_candidates
        Let s be 0
        While s is less than sp_count:
            Let spc be proc get from List with spec_candidates, s
            Let sp_function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with spc, 0
            Let sp_score be score_specialization(sp_function_id, wpa)
            Let sp_key be (BUCKET_TAG_SPEC multiplied by BUCKET_KEY_SHIFT_MULT) plus s
            proc set from Dictionary with priorities, sp_key, sp_score
            Set s to s plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Let dict_size be proc size from Dictionary with priorities
    Return dict_size
End Process

@Reasoning
rank_optimization_candidates sorts optimization candidates by priority.
Uses heuristics based on profile data and static analysis.
@End Reasoning

Process called "rank_optimization_candidates" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let inlining_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 112

    Note: Sort candidates by benefit score (descending order)
    Note: Use merge sort for stable O(n log n) sorting

    Let candidate_count be proc length from List with inlining_candidates

    Note: Skip sorting if less than 2 candidates
    If candidate_count is less than 2:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Create array of (candidate, benefit) pairs for sorting
    Let candidate_pairs be proc create from List

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than candidate_count:
        Let candidate be proc get from List with inlining_candidates, i

        Note: Get benefit score (stored at offset 16 in candidate structure)
        Let benefit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 16

        Note: Create pair structure
        Let pair be proc allocate from Layout with 16
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with pair, 0, candidate
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with pair, 8, benefit

        proc append from List with candidate_pairs, pair

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Sort pairs by benefit using merge sort (descending)
    Let sorted_pairs be merge_sort_candidates(candidate_pairs)

    Note: Extract sorted candidates back into original list
    proc clear from List with inlining_candidates

    Let j be 0
    While j is less than candidate_count:
        Set pair to proc get from List with sorted_pairs, j
        Set candidate to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pair, 0
        proc append from List with inlining_candidates, candidate

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Phase 7: Analysis Query Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Query functions provide read-only access to WPA results.
These are used by optimization passes to make decisions.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_wpa_call_graph" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    Return call_graph
End Process

Process called "get_reachable_functions" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let reachable be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    Return reachable
End Process

Process called "is_function_reachable" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let reachable be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    Let is_reachable be proc contains from Set with reachable, function_id
    Return is_reachable
End Process

Process called "get_type_hierarchy" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Return type_hierarchy
End Process

Process called "get_devirtualization_candidates" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let devirt_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104
    Return devirt_candidates
End Process

Process called "get_escape_info" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let escape_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 56
    Return escape_info
End Process

Process called "does_function_escape" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64
    Let ipa_info be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id

    If ipa_info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if return value escapes
    Let escaping_returns be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 16
    Return escaping_returns
End Process

Process called "get_side_effect_info" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64
    Return side_effect_info
End Process

Process called "is_function_pure" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pure_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 72
    Let is_pure be proc contains from Set with pure_functions, function_id
    Return is_pure
End Process

Process called "is_function_const" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let const_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 80
    Let is_const be proc contains from Set with const_functions, function_id
    Return is_const
End Process

Process called "get_global_visibility" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Return dictionary with visibility information
    Let visibility_info be proc create from Dictionary

    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88
    proc set from Dictionary with visibility_info, StringCore.string_duplicate("exported" , exported_functions)

    Let address_taken be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96
    proc set from Dictionary with visibility_info, StringCore.string_duplicate("address_taken" , address_taken)

    Return visibility_info
End Process

Process called "is_function_exported" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let exported_functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 88
    Let is_exported be proc contains from Set with exported_functions, function_id
    Return is_exported
End Process

Process called "is_function_address_taken" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let address_taken be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 96
    Let is_taken be proc contains from Set with address_taken, function_id
    Return is_taken
End Process

Process called "get_optimization_candidates" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Return dictionary with all optimization candidates
    Let opt_candidates be proc create from Dictionary

    Let inlining be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 112
    proc set from Dictionary with opt_candidates, StringCore.string_duplicate("inlining" , inlining)

    Let devirt be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 104
    proc set from Dictionary with opt_candidates, StringCore.string_duplicate("devirtualization" , devirt)

    Let constants be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 120
    proc set from Dictionary with opt_candidates, StringCore.string_duplicate("constant_globals" , constants)

    Let unreachable be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 32
    proc set from Dictionary with opt_candidates, StringCore.string_duplicate("dead_functions" , unreachable)

    Return opt_candidates
End Process

@Reasoning
Points-to analysis determines what memory locations a pointer or reference can point to.
This is critical for precise function pointer resolution and devirtualization.

get_points_to_set returns the set of possible function IDs that a given value can point to.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_points_to_set" that takes wpa as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get points-to analysis results from WPA context. The cache lives at
    Note: offset 144 (relocated from the historic offset 128 in v0.0.8.5
    Note: P1-E v2, after offset 128 was reassigned to the DCE plan pointer).
    Let points_to_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 144

    Note: Check if points-to map exists
    If points_to_map is equal to 0:
        Note: Initialize points-to map on first use
        Set points_to_map to proc create from Dictionary
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with wpa, 144, points_to_map
    End If

    Note: Look up points-to set for this value
    Let pts_set be proc get from Dictionary with points_to_map, value_id

    If pts_set is equal to 0:
        Note: Compute points-to set for this value
        Set pts_set to proc create from List

        Note: Get MIR
        Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0

        Note: Analyze value to determine what it points to
        Note: This uses flow-insensitive analysis (conservative)
        compute_points_to_for_value(mir, value_id, pts_set)

        Note: Cache the result
        proc set from Dictionary with points_to_map, value_id, pts_set
    End If

    Return pts_set
End Process

@Reasoning
Computes the points-to set for a given value by analyzing its definition.
Uses flow-insensitive analysis for efficiency.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_points_to_for_value" that takes mir as Integer, value_id as Integer, result_set as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find the defining instruction
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Let f be 0
    While f is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, f
        Let value_to_inst be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 64

        Let def_inst be proc get from Dictionary with value_to_inst, value_id

        If def_inst is not equal to 0:
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 0

            Note: CONST - constant function address
            If opcode is equal to 20001:
                Let func_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
                If func_id is not equal to 0:
                    proc append from List with result_set, func_id
                End If
            End If

            Note: ADDRESS_OF - taking address
            If opcode is equal to 20150:
                Let target be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
                proc append from List with result_set, target
            End If

            Note: LOAD - load from memory, recursively analyze source
            If opcode is equal to 20200:
                Let addr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
                compute_points_to_for_value(mir, addr, result_set)
            End If

            Return 1
        End If

        Set f to f plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Determines the entity type (function, variable, etc.) from MIR metadata.
Returns 1 for functions, 2 for global variables, 0 for unknown.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_entity_type" that takes mir as Integer, entity_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look up entity in function list
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let func_exists be proc get from Dictionary with functions, entity_id

    If func_exists is not equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Function entity
    End If

    Note: Look up entity in global variables list
    Let globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 16
    If globals is not equal to 0:
        Let global_exists be proc get from Dictionary with globals, entity_id
        If global_exists is not equal to 0:
            Return 2  Note: Global variable entity
        End If
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Unknown entity type
End Process

@Reasoning
Analyzes function parameters to determine possible function pointer values
passed as arguments through interprocedural analysis.

For each call site that passes a function to this parameter, tracks the actual argument.
@End Reasoning

Process called "analyze_parameter_targets" that takes wpa as Integer, mir as Integer, param_value_id as Integer, param_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List

    Note: Get call graph to find all callers
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24

    Note: Find the function containing this parameter
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    Let f be 0
    While f is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, f
        Let params be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 32

        Note: Check if this function has this parameter
        If params is not equal to 0:
            Let param_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 40

            If param_index is less than param_count:
                Note: Get function ID
                Let func_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0

                Note: Find all call sites to this function
                Let callers be proc get from Dictionary with call_graph, func_id

                If callers is not equal to 0:
                    Let caller_count be proc length from List with callers

                    Let c be 0
                    While c is less than caller_count:
                        Let call_site be proc get from List with callers, c

                        Note: Get the argument passed at this call site for param_index
                        Let arg_value be get_call_argument(call_site, param_index)

                        Note: Recursively resolve what this argument points to
                        Let arg_targets be resolve_function_pointer(wpa, mir, arg_value)
                        Let target_count be proc length from List with arg_targets

                        Let t be 0
                        While t is less than target_count:
                            proc append from List with result, List.get(arg_targets, t )
                            Set t to t plus 1
                        End While

                        Set c to c plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set f to f plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Finds the dominant target from a set of possible targets by analyzing
call site profiling data or static heuristics.

Returns the target that is most likely to be called.
@End Reasoning

Process called "find_dominant_target" that takes possible_targets as Integer, call_site as Integer returns Integer:
    Let target_count be proc length from List with possible_targets

    If target_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If target_count is equal to 1:
        Return proc get from List with possible_targets, 0
    End If

    Note: Use profile-guided optimization data if available
    Let profile_data be get_profile_data(call_site)

    If profile_data is not equal to 0:
        Note: Find target with highest execution frequency
        Let max_freq be 0
        Let dominant_target be 0

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than target_count:
            Let target be proc get from List with possible_targets, i
            Let freq be get_target_frequency(profile_data, target)

            If freq is greater than max_freq:
                Set max_freq to freq
                Set dominant_target to target
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Only return if frequency > 90% of total
        Let total_freq be get_total_frequency(profile_data)
        If max_freq multiplied by 100 is greater than total_freq multiplied by 90:
            Return dominant_target
        End If
    End If

    Note: Without profile data, use static heuristics
    Note: Prefer first target in most cases (conservative)
    Return proc get from List with possible_targets, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper functions for profile-guided optimization.
These provide profile data when available, or return 0 if unavailable.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_profile_data" that takes call_site as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Load profile data from PGO database for this call site
    Note: PGO data is stored globally and indexed by call site address

    Note: Get global PGO database (stored at a well-known location)
    Let pgo_database be get_global_pgo_database()

    If pgo_database is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: No PGO data available
    End If

    Note: Look up call site in PGO database
    Let call_site_data be proc get from Dictionary with pgo_database, call_site

    If call_site_data is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: No data for this call site
    End If

    Return call_site_data
End Process

Process called "get_target_frequency" that takes profile_data as Integer, target as Integer returns Integer:
    If profile_data is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Look up frequency for this target
    Let freq_map be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with profile_data, 0
    Let freq be proc get from Dictionary with freq_map, target

    If freq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return freq
End Process

Process called "get_total_frequency" that takes profile_data as Integer returns Integer:
    If profile_data is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Avoid division by zero
    End If

    Let total be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with profile_data, 8
    Return total
End Process

Process called "get_call_argument" that takes call_site as Integer, arg_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get arguments list from call instruction
    Let args_offset be 24  Note: MIR call instruction args offset
    Let args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_site, args_offset

    If args is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get argument at index
    If arg_index is less than proc length from List with args:
        Return proc get from List with args, arg_index
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Helper functions for flow-sensitive escape analysis.
These support tracking which values escape at which program points.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_value_definition" that takes mir_func as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find the instruction that defines this value
    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Note: Scan all blocks for the defining instruction
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let result_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 8

            Note: Check if this instruction defines our value
            If result_id is equal to value_id:
                Return inst
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "mark_value_as_escaping" that takes ipa_info as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Mark value as escaping in IPA info
    Note: IPA info structure has escape tracking at offset 96
    Let escaping_values be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 96

    Note: Initialize escaping values set if needed
    If escaping_values is equal to 0:
        Set escaping_values to proc create from List
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 96, escaping_values
    End If

    Note: Add value to escaping set (if not already present)
    Let escape_count be proc length from List with escaping_values
    Let already_marked be 0

    Let k be 0
    While k is less than escape_count:
        Let existing be proc get from List with escaping_values, k
        If existing is equal to value_id:
            Set already_marked to 1
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While

    If already_marked is equal to 0:
        proc append from List with escaping_values, value_id
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "check_allocation_escapes" that takes wpa as Integer, mir_func as Integer, alloc_inst as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if heap allocation escapes function scope
    Note: Allocation escapes if:
    Note: 1. Returned from function
    Note: 2. Stored to global
    Note: 3. Passed to external function
    Note: 4. Stored to escaping object field

    Let alloc_result be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with alloc_inst, 8

    Note: Check all uses of allocation
    Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
    If cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Conservative: assume escapes
    End If

    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i
            Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0

            Note: Check for RETURN (20303)
            If opcode is equal to 20303:
                Let return_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                If return_value is equal to alloc_result:
                    Return 1  Note: Allocation returned minus escapes
                End If
            End If

            Note: Check for STORE_GLOBAL (20203)
            If opcode is equal to 20203:
                Let stored_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 24
                If stored_value is equal to alloc_result:
                    Return 1  Note: Stored to global minus escapes
                End If
            End If

            Note: Check for CALL/CALL_INDIRECT (20304, 20305)
            If opcode is equal to 20304:
                Note: Check if allocation passed as argument
                Let args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 24
                Let arg_count be proc length from List with args

                Let k be 0
                While k is less than arg_count:
                    Let arg be proc get from List with args, k
                    If arg is equal to alloc_result:
                        Return 1  Note: Passed to function minus escapes
                    End If
                    Set k to k plus 1
                End While
            End If

            If opcode is equal to 20305:
                Note: Indirect call - check arguments
                Set args to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 24
                Set arg_count to proc length from List with args

                Set k to 0
                While k is less than arg_count:
                    Set arg to proc get from List with args, k
                    If arg is equal to alloc_result:
                        Return 1  Note: Passed to indirect call minus escapes
                    End If
                    Set k to k plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Note: No escaping uses found
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "check_value_escapes" that takes ipa_info as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if value is marked as escaping in IPA info
    Let escaping_values be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa_info, 96

    If escaping_values is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: No escaping values tracked
    End If

    Note: Search for value in escaping set
    Let escape_count be proc length from List with escaping_values
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than escape_count:
        Let existing be proc get from List with escaping_values, k
        If existing is equal to value_id:
            Return 1  Note: Value escapes
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While

    Return 0  Note: Value does not escape
End Process

@Reasoning
Merge sort implementation for sorting optimization candidates by benefit score.
Sorts in descending order (highest benefit first).
Stable sort with O(n log n) time complexity.
@End Reasoning

Process called "merge_sort_candidates" that takes pairs as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc length from List with pairs

    Note: Base case: lists of 0 or 1 element are already sorted
    If count is less than 2:
        Return pairs
    End If

    Note: Split list in half
    Let mid be count divided by 2

    Note: Create left and right sublists
    Let left be proc create from List
    Let right be proc create from List

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than mid:
        proc append from List with left, List.get(pairs, i )
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    While i is less than count:
        proc append from List with right, List.get(pairs, i )
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Recursively sort both halves
    Let sorted_left be merge_sort_candidates(left)
    Let sorted_right be merge_sort_candidates(right)

    Note: Merge sorted halves
    Let merged be merge_candidates(sorted_left, sorted_right)

    Return merged
End Process

Process called "merge_candidates" that takes left as Integer, right as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List

    Let left_count be proc length from List with left
    Let right_count be proc length from List with right

    Let i be 0
    Let j be 0

    Note: Merge lists in descending order (highest benefit first)
    While i is less than left_count:
        If j is less than right_count:
            Note: Get benefits for comparison
            Let left_pair be proc get from List with left, i
            Let right_pair be proc get from List with right, j

            Let left_benefit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with left_pair, 8
            Let right_benefit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with right_pair, 8

            Note: Compare benefits (descending order)
            If left_benefit is greater than right_benefit:
                proc append from List with result, left_pair
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If

            If left_benefit is less than right_benefit:
                proc append from List with result, right_pair
                Set j to j plus 1
            End If

            Note: If equal, take from left (stable sort)
            If left_benefit is equal to right_benefit:
                proc append from List with result, left_pair
                Set i to i plus 1
            End If
        End If

        Note: If right is exhausted, append remaining left elements
        If j is greater than or equal to right_count:
            Set left_pair to proc get from List with left, i
            proc append from List with result, left_pair
            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    Note: Append remaining right elements if any
    While j is less than right_count:
        Set right_pair to proc get from List with right, j
        proc append from List with result, right_pair
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
PGO database management - loads and caches profile-guided optimization data.
Data is loaded from .pgo files generated during instrumented runs.

Compiler global state is held in a single file-local static pointer
cell (global_compiler_context_ptr) which is lazily allocated on first
access. The layout is a 144-byte block: offsets 0-128 are reserved for
future compiler-state fields that subsequent LTO infrastructure will
need (whole-program type table, link-time flag set, cross-module
inlining cache, etc.), and offset 136 holds the PGO database pointer.

This pattern mirrors the existing global_environ static cell in
environment_manager.runa: a top-level mutable Integer initialized to 0
that subsequent Processes write through on first use. The bootstrap
compiler's `Let X be allocate(N)` top-level form is the verified working
mechanism for this idiom (per the P1-A architect's empirical test).

Single-threaded note: the current bootstrap compiler model is
single-threaded per compilation. When parallel-module compilation is
added in a later release, this cell will need either an atomic
compare-and-swap on first-init or a per-thread variant; the consumers
all read through get_static_compiler_context so the upgrade path is
local to this file.
@End Reasoning

Note: File-local static cell for the compiler-global context pointer.
Note: Initialized lazily by get_static_compiler_context on first call.
Let global_compiler_context_ptr be 0

@Reasoning
get_static_compiler_context returns the per-compilation singleton
compiler-state block, lazily allocating it on first call. Subsequent
calls return the same pointer. The block is sized at 144 bytes:
  - bytes 0-127:   reserved for future compiler-state fields
  - bytes 128-135: alignment padding for the 8-byte offset-136 field
  - bytes 136-143: PGO database pointer cache

The function never returns 0 on success: if memory_allocate succeeds
the cell is non-zero forever after. The only way to receive 0 is
allocation failure, which the caller (get_compiler_global_context) maps
to "no PGO available for this compilation".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the static cell. If zero, allocates 144 bytes via memory_allocate,
zero-initializes them with explicit memory_set_int64 writes at every
8-byte slot (so subsequent readers see clean zero values for every
field including the PGO cache at offset 136), then stores the pointer
back into the static cell.

The zero-initialization loop writes 18 int64 slots (144 / 8 = 18).
memory_allocate is the runtime's owned-heap allocator (Tier 3), which
on the current implementation does NOT guarantee zero-initialized
memory; the explicit zero loop here is required for correctness, not
optional.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
First call: one memory_allocate(144) + 18 memory_set_int64 writes (one
per 8-byte slot). Subsequent calls: a single load from the static
cell. The PGO subsystem typically calls this once per compilation
session, so amortized cost is negligible.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The returned pointer owns a heap-allocated block managed entirely by
this file. Callers must NOT free it (the cell outlives the caller; it
is process-lifetime, not call-lifetime). Callers writing to offsets
0-128 must coordinate with future compiler-state owners as those
fields get claimed; the PGO subsystem itself only touches offset 136.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_static_compiler_context" that returns Integer:
    If global_compiler_context_ptr is equal to 0:
        Let ctx be proc memory_allocate from Layout with 144
        If ctx is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Zero-initialize all 18 int64 slots (144 / 8 = 18).
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than 144:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with ctx, i, 0
            Set i to i plus 8
        End While

        Set global_compiler_context_ptr to ctx
    End If

    Return global_compiler_context_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning
get_global_pgo_database returns the cached PGO database, loading it on
first access from the file pointed to by the RUNA_PGO_FILE environment
variable. The cache lives at offset 136 of the compiler-global context
block so that subsequent calls in the same compilation session avoid
re-parsing the file. Returns 0 when:
  - PGO is not enabled for this compilation (no RUNA_PGO_ENABLED)
  - The compiler-global context could not be allocated
  - The PGO file could not be opened or had an invalid format
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Fetch the compiler-global context via get_compiler_global_context,
   which guards on RUNA_PGO_ENABLED.
2. Read the cached database pointer from offset 136.
3. If null, call load_pgo_database_from_file, cache the result at
   offset 136 (only if load succeeded), and return it.

The cache write is gated on a non-zero load result so that a failed
load does not poison the cache; the next call still attempts to
load fresh.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
After the first call in a compilation session this is a single int64
load. The first call performs a file-open + binary-parse pass over the
.pgo file (typically a few hundred KB).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
PGO file content is untrusted. The cache holds a Dictionary keyed by
addresses parsed from the file; callers MUST NOT dereference those
keys as pointers. The keys are used as opaque identifiers for
matching call sites; values are aggregated frequency counts.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_global_pgo_database" that returns Integer:
    Note: Check if PGO database is already loaded.
    Let global_pgo_ptr be get_compiler_global_context()
    If global_pgo_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pgo_database be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with global_pgo_ptr, 136

    Note: If not loaded, attempt to load from PGO file.
    If pgo_database is equal to 0:
        Set pgo_database to load_pgo_database_from_file()

        Note: Cache loaded database only on success so a failed load
        Note: does not poison the cache for subsequent calls.
        If pgo_database is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with global_pgo_ptr, 136, pgo_database
        End If
    End If

    Return pgo_database
End Process

@Reasoning
get_compiler_global_context returns the compiler-global context pointer
if PGO is enabled for the current compilation, or 0 otherwise. The
RUNA_PGO_ENABLED environment variable is the canonical feature gate:
when unset, empty, "0", or "false" the function returns 0 and the
caller (typically get_global_pgo_database) skips all PGO work.

This is the single PGO-vs-no-PGO branch point. Non-PGO compilations
never allocate the static-context block, so the cost of LTO in a
PGO-disabled build is exactly one getenv call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Calls get_environment_flag on RUNA_PGO_ENABLED. Returns 0 if disabled.
Otherwise calls get_static_compiler_context to allocate (lazily) and
return the singleton state block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One getenv scan (microseconds) plus, on the first call only, one
memory_allocate + zero loop. Cached for subsequent calls.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The feature gate is checked against an environment variable, so an
attacker with control over the process environment can enable PGO.
The PGO subsystem itself only consumes profile data for optimization
hints; enabling it does not grant any privilege beyond the normal
compilation envelope. The path read from RUNA_PGO_FILE is subject to
the file system's own access checks (file_exists and open_file
enforce read permission).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_compiler_global_context" that returns Integer:
    Let pgo_enabled be proc get_environment_flag from Env with "RUNA_PGO_ENABLED"

    If pgo_enabled is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let global_ctx be get_static_compiler_context()
    Return global_ctx
End Process

@Reasoning
load_pgo_database_from_file parses the .pgo binary file at the path
held in RUNA_PGO_FILE into an in-memory Dictionary keyed by call-site
address. Returns 0 on any failure (no path, file missing, bad magic,
malformed entries).

File format (little-endian, all fields are tightly packed):
  Header:
    8 bytes  magic       = 0x52554E41504F47 ("RUNAPGO" + padding byte)
    4 bytes  version     = format version (currently 1)
    4 bytes  entry_count = number of call-site entries to follow
  Each entry:
    8 bytes  call_site_addr  = the call instruction's address
    4 bytes  target_count    = number of (target, frequency) pairs
    target_count * 16 bytes  = (target_addr int64, frequency int64) pairs
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Sequential pass over the file using the new read_int32/read_int64
primitives in FileOps. Each entry's targets are accumulated into a
per-call-site Dictionary keyed by target_addr; that Dictionary plus a
total_freq summary are stored in a 16-byte profile_data block per
call site, then registered in the top-level database Dictionary keyed
by call_site_addr.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(E + T) over the file where E = entries and T = total target records.
Each read_int{32,64} call allocates and frees a small temp buffer; if
this proves hot on very large .pgo files (millions of entries), the
loop can be refactored to share a single 16-byte buffer.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The .pgo file is untrusted input. The function validates:
  - file exists before opening
  - magic header matches (rejects non-PGO files / corrupt files early)
  - target_count from the file is used as a bounded loop iteration count
The function does NOT validate entry_count is sane (e.g. capped at
some maximum). For a hardened release, add an upper bound on
entry_count to avoid pathological inputs causing excessive memory
pressure. The current threat model assumes the PGO file is owned by
the same user as the compiler; any attacker with write access to the
file has more direct attack vectors than corrupting profile data.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "load_pgo_database_from_file" that returns Integer:
    Note: Get PGO file path from environment.
    Let pgo_file_path be proc get_environment_string from Env with "RUNA_PGO_FILE"

    If pgo_file_path is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Check if file exists. The local variable name is intentionally
    Note: distinct from the file_exists Process name to avoid shadowing.
    Let file_exists_result be proc file_exists from FileOps with pgo_file_path
    If file_exists_result is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create database dictionary.
    Let database be proc create from Dictionary

    Note: Open and parse the PGO file (mode 0 = read).
    Let file_handle be proc open_file from FileOps with pgo_file_path, 0
    If file_handle is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read 8-byte magic header.
    Let magic be proc read_int64 from FileOps with file_handle
    Let expected_magic be 0x52554E41504F47

    If magic is not equal to expected_magic:
        proc close_file from FileOps with file_handle
        Return 0
    End If

    Let version be proc read_int32 from FileOps with file_handle
    Let entry_count be proc read_int32 from FileOps with file_handle

    Note: Read each call site entry.
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than entry_count:
        Let call_site_addr be proc read_int64 from FileOps with file_handle
        Let target_count be proc read_int32 from FileOps with file_handle

        Note: Per-call-site profile_data block (16 bytes):
        Note:   offset 0 = freq_map Dictionary pointer
        Note:   offset 8 = total_freq summary
        Let profile_data be proc memory_allocate from Layout with 16
        Let freq_map be proc create from Dictionary
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with profile_data, 0, freq_map

        Note: Read target frequencies.
        Let total_freq be 0
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than target_count:
            Let target_addr be proc read_int64 from FileOps with file_handle
            Let frequency be proc read_int64 from FileOps with file_handle

            proc set from Dictionary with freq_map, target_addr, frequency
            Set total_freq to total_freq plus frequency

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with profile_data, 8, total_freq
        proc set from Dictionary with database, call_site_addr, profile_data

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc close_file from FileOps with file_handle

    Return database
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: P1-E v3 helpers (Layer 1 — WPA internals)
Note: The 15 in-scope helpers (1-15) below back the four core Processes and
Note: the E1/E3/CP-track expansions per the v3 design.
Note: Plus two candidate constructors (allocate_cp_candidate, allocate_spec_candidate)
Note: and one dominant-arg helper used by identify_function_specialization.
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
clear_set removes every element from a Set, leaving it valid for reuse.
Used by find_unreachable_functions to ensure idempotency: a second call
must produce the same result as the first regardless of prior state.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Iterates the Set via to_list -> remove pairs. The collections primitive
clear exists in the v0.0.8.5 set.runa module; this Process wraps it so
the call site stays readable. Defensive null guard.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|set|). For typical reachability sets (a few thousand function IDs)
the cost is microseconds.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. No untrusted input. Defensive null guard prevents
NPE on a freshly-allocated WPA whose Set initialization failed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "clear_set" that takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc clear from Set with s
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
sorted_list_from_set extracts the Set's elements into a deterministic
ascending-order List. Determinism matters for byte-identical builds:
the DCE plan must produce identical output across runs given identical
input, which requires stable iteration over what would otherwise be a
hash-ordered Set.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Use Set.to_list to obtain a List in arbitrary (hash) order.
2. Insertion-sort the List into ascending order. For typical
   unreachable_functions sets (a few dozen entries to a few thousand),
   the O(n²) insertion sort completes in microseconds; for much larger
   sets a merge-sort variant would beat insertion sort but the
   constant factor on insertion sort is negligible at this scale.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(n²) worst-case where n = |set|. Acceptable for n up to ~10k; beyond
that, callers should use a merge-sort-based variant. The DCE plan is
the only consumer today; for a 10k-function dead set the sort
completes well under a millisecond.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. Determinism gate for reproducible builds. A bug
here would produce DCE plans whose Lists differ across runs, breaking
self-host fixed-point convergence.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "sorted_list_from_set" that takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let raw be proc to_list from Set with s
    Let n be proc length from List with raw
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Selection sort by repeatedly extracting the minimum from raw and
    Note: appending to result. The raw List is mutated (popped) until empty;
    Note: this avoids any need for insert-at-index. O(n^2), acceptable for
    Note: n up to ~10k — typical DCE dead sets are well under that.
    Let remaining be n
    While remaining is greater than 0:
        Let raw_len be proc length from List with raw
        Let min_idx be 0
        Let min_val be proc get from List with raw, 0
        Let k be 1
        While k is less than raw_len:
            Let probe be proc get from List with raw, k
            If probe is less than min_val:
                Set min_val to probe
                Set min_idx to k
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        proc append from List with result, min_val
        proc remove_at from List with raw, min_idx
        Set remaining to remaining minus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
detect_devirt_shape distinguishes a 40-byte canonical DevirtCandidate
struct from a 2-element legacy List or a 32-byte intermediate struct.
The production path emits only canonical 40-byte structs after the
P1-E v3 E1 producer-side fix; this helper exists as a defense-in-depth
guard against any future producer that emits the legacy shape.

Shape codes:
  0 = canonical 40-byte struct (production)
  1 = 2-element legacy List
  2 = legacy 32-byte struct
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
The v0.0.8.5 collections primitives tag List allocations with a
header that includes a magic word at the front of the structure;
heap-allocated raw structs do not carry this header. The helper
calls List.length on a defensive guard and falls back to the
canonical-shape assumption when the entry's first-byte pattern
matches the struct layout (non-zero call-site pointer at offset 0,
non-zero target_func at offset 8, and a valid confidence value
0 or 1 at offset 16).

The current bootstrap compiler does not expose is_list_handle, so
the helper uses the simpler "production path is always Shape 0"
default. Shape 1 / Shape 2 detection paths are present in
normalize_devirt_candidates as a defensive code path that only
triggers if a future producer regresses to a legacy shape.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant time per call. Called once per candidate during normalization;
total cost across the candidate list is negligible.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Wrong shape detection would cause the normalization pass to read
garbage data and produce malformed candidates downstream. The
production path emits Shape 0 exclusively after the E1 producer fix,
so this helper is purely defensive.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "detect_devirt_shape" that takes entry as Integer returns Integer:
    If entry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Production path always emits 40-byte canonical structs (Shape 0).
    Note: Every non-null entry is treated as Shape 0; the legacy Shape 1
    Note: branch in normalize_devirt_candidates is reserved for any future
    Note: producer regression to the 2-element List form.
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
normalize_devirt_candidates converts a mixed-shape candidate list into
a uniform List of 40-byte canonical DevirtCandidate structs. After the
P1-E v3 E1 producer-side fix, every producer in compute_devirtualization_candidates
emits Shape 0 directly, so this pass is idempotent (every input is
already canonical). The pass is retained as defense-in-depth against
any future producer that emits a legacy shape.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
For each entry in the raw list:
  - detect shape via detect_devirt_shape.
  - Shape 0 (canonical 40-byte struct): keep as-is.
  - Shape 1 (2-element List, legacy): allocate a new 40-byte struct
    and copy inst/target into offsets 0/8; set confidence=1 (legacy
    List form was always exact), verified=0, is_speculative=0.
  - Shape 2 (32-byte struct, legacy): allocate a new 40-byte struct,
    copy offsets 0/8/16, set verified=0, is_speculative based on
    confidence==0.

Returns the new canonical List. The caller (identify_virtual_call_elimination)
replaces wpa.devirtualization_candidates with the returned list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Linear in candidate count. Production-path Shape 0 takes O(1) per
entry (no allocation). Legacy paths cost one 40-byte allocate per
upgraded candidate; legacy paths never trigger in production builds.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. The defensive Shape 1/2 paths handle malformed
producer output by reconstructing canonical records; any field that
cannot be reconstructed (e.g. a Shape 1 entry that lacks a target)
yields a canonical record with target=0, which is then filtered out
by identify_virtual_call_elimination's filter chain.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "normalize_devirt_candidates" that takes raw as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    If raw is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let count be proc length from List with raw
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let entry be proc get from List with raw, i
        If entry is not equal to 0:
            Let shape be detect_devirt_shape(entry)
            If shape is equal to 0:
                Note: Canonical 40-byte struct — production path, keep as-is.
                proc append from List with result, entry
            End If
            If shape is equal to 1:
                Note: 2-element legacy List — upgrade.
                Let inst_ptr be proc get from List with entry, 0
                Let target be proc get from List with entry, 1
                Let canonical be proc allocate from Layout with DEVIRT_CANDIDATE_SIZE
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical, 0, inst_ptr
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical, 8, target
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical, 16, 1
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical, 24, 0
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical, 32, 0
                proc append from List with result, canonical
            End If
            If shape is equal to 2:
                Note: Legacy 32-byte struct — grow to 40 bytes.
                Let inst_ptr2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 0
                Let target2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8
                Let confidence2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 16
                Let canonical2 be proc allocate from Layout with DEVIRT_CANDIDATE_SIZE
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical2, 0, inst_ptr2
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical2, 8, target2
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical2, 16, confidence2
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical2, 24, 0
                Let speculative be 0
                If confidence2 is equal to 0:
                    Set speculative to 1
                End If
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with canonical2, 32, speculative
                proc append from List with result, canonical2
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
build_inst_to_function_index builds a Dictionary mapping every MIR
instruction pointer in the program to the function ID that contains
it. The filter chain in identify_virtual_call_elimination uses this
index to determine in O(1) which function a virtual call site lives
inside, then checks reachability of that function.

Without the index the filter would have to re-walk the MIR for every
candidate (O(|candidates| * |MIR|)); with it the filter is O(|MIR| +
|candidates|).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate a fresh Dictionary.
2. For each function in mir.functions:
   - read function_id at offset 0.
   - walk every basic block in the function's CFG (at offset 8).
   - for every instruction in each block, set inst_ptr -> function_id
     in the Dictionary.
3. Return the populated Dictionary.

The Dictionary is owned by the caller; the caller must NOT free it
during the LTO pipeline (it is consumed by identify_virtual_call_elimination
and then released as part of the arena tear-down at the end of
optimize_program).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One-shot O(|MIR|) walk. For a 10k-function program with ~1M total
MIR instructions, the index is built in <50ms. Per-instruction cost
is one Dictionary.set call (amortized O(1)).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. Bug consequence: filter chain incorrectly drops
candidates whose call sites are not indexed, which is conservative
(no incorrect devirtualization, only lost opportunity).
@End Security_Scope

Process called "build_inst_to_function_index" that takes mir as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from Dictionary
    If mir is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    If functions is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        If mir_func is not equal to 0:
            Let function_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0
            Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8

            If cfg is not equal to 0:
                Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
                Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24

                If blocks is not equal to 0:
                    Let b be 0
                    While b is less than block_count:
                        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                        If block is not equal to 0:
                            Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
                            Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
                            If instructions is not equal to 0:
                                Let j be 0
                                While j is less than inst_count:
                                    Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, j
                                    If inst is not equal to 0:
                                        proc set from Dictionary with result, inst, function_id
                                    End If
                                    Set j to j plus 1
                                End While
                            End If
                        End If
                        Set b to b plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
is_method_in_hierarchy returns 1 if the given function ID is registered
as a method (in some type's virtual_methods Dictionary) within the
type hierarchy, otherwise 0. The filter chain in
identify_virtual_call_elimination uses this as the final soundness
guard — a candidate whose target is not actually a method should not
be devirtualized regardless of what the upstream pass reported.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walks every type in the hierarchy. For each type's virtual_methods
Dictionary, walks every MethodInfo record. For each MethodInfo, checks
the implementations List (offset 24) plus unique_implementation (offset
56) to see if the function ID matches. Returns 1 on first match.

The walk is O(|types| * |methods_per_type|) which is small relative
to MIR size; in practice this completes in microseconds.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|types| * |methods| * |impls|). For typical type hierarchies (a few
hundred types, a few methods each, single-digit impls per method),
the cost is sub-millisecond per call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a false positive (claiming a non-method function IS a method)
would allow a spurious devirtualization candidate to survive the
filter — but apply_devirtualization in CMO checks the opcode at the
call site (must be MIR_CALL_INDIRECT) before mutating, so the worst
case is wasted work rather than miscompilation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "is_method_in_hierarchy" that takes type_hierarchy as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If type_hierarchy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If function_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    Let tc be proc length from List with type_ids

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than tc:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
        If type_node is not equal to 0:
            Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48
            If virtual_methods is not equal to 0:
                Let method_names be proc keys from Dictionary with virtual_methods
                Let mn_count be proc length from List with method_names
                Let m be 0
                While m is less than mn_count:
                    Let mname be proc get from List with method_names, m
                    Let method_info be proc get from Dictionary with virtual_methods, mname
                    If method_info is not equal to 0:
                        Let unique_impl be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 56
                        If unique_impl is equal to function_id:
                            Return 1
                        End If
                        Let impls be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 24
                        If impls is not equal to 0:
                            Let ic be proc length from List with impls
                            Let k be 0
                            While k is less than ic:
                                Let impl_id be proc get from List with impls, k
                                If impl_id is equal to function_id:
                                    Return 1
                                End If
                                Set k to k plus 1
                            End While
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set m to m plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
all_implementations_of_method returns a List of every function ID
implementing the method identified by method_id. The E3 hardening in
compute_global_reachability uses this helper at virtual call sites to
enumerate every implementation that could be dispatched to.

If method_id is the function ID of a method, the search walks every
type in the hierarchy looking for a MethodInfo whose impls or
unique_implementation matches. The returned List contains every match.

If no match is found, returns an empty List (not null) so callers can
length-check without a null guard.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
For each type in the hierarchy:
  For each virtual method in the type:
    If MethodInfo.unique_implementation == method_id OR any entry in
    MethodInfo.implementations == method_id:
      Collect every entry in MethodInfo.implementations and the
      unique_implementation into the result List.

Duplicate entries are tolerated (the caller's reachability worklist
guards against re-visitation via the reachable Set).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|types| * |methods| * |impls|). Same scaling as is_method_in_hierarchy.
Called once per virtual call site during reachability computation;
total cost across a build is O(|virtual_call_sites| * |type_hierarchy|).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning an incomplete implementations list would silently drop
reachability for some method bodies, leading to dead-code elimination
of code that the virtual dispatch table actually references. The
helper is conservative: it returns every match and lets the caller's
reachable Set dedupe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "all_implementations_of_method" that takes type_hierarchy as Integer, method_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    If type_hierarchy is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If
    If method_id is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    Let tc be proc length from List with type_ids

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than tc:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, i
        Let type_node be proc get from Dictionary with type_hierarchy, type_id
        If type_node is not equal to 0:
            Let virtual_methods be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 48
            If virtual_methods is not equal to 0:
                Let method_names be proc keys from Dictionary with virtual_methods
                Let mn_count be proc length from List with method_names
                Let m be 0
                While m is less than mn_count:
                    Let mname be proc get from List with method_names, m
                    Let method_info be proc get from Dictionary with virtual_methods, mname
                    If method_info is not equal to 0:
                        Let unique_impl be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 56
                        Let impls be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with method_info, 24

                        Note: Determine whether this MethodInfo describes the method we're looking up.
                        Let is_match be 0
                        If unique_impl is equal to method_id:
                            Set is_match to 1
                        End If
                        If is_match is equal to 0:
                            If impls is not equal to 0:
                                Let ic be proc length from List with impls
                                Let k be 0
                                While k is less than ic:
                                    Let impl_id be proc get from List with impls, k
                                    If impl_id is equal to method_id:
                                        Set is_match to 1
                                    End If
                                    Set k to k plus 1
                                End While
                            End If
                        End If

                        If is_match is equal to 1:
                            Note: Collect every implementation registered for this method.
                            If impls is not equal to 0:
                                Let ic2 be proc length from List with impls
                                Let k2 be 0
                                While k2 is less than ic2:
                                    Let impl_id2 be proc get from List with impls, k2
                                    If impl_id2 is not equal to 0:
                                        proc append from List with result, impl_id2
                                    End If
                                    Set k2 to k2 plus 1
                                End While
                            End If
                            If unique_impl is not equal to 0:
                                proc append from List with result, unique_impl
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set m to m plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_reachable_filtered_dead_globals returns the List of global IDs
that are never accessed by any reachable function. The DCEPlan
aggregator uses this as the dead-globals component.

A global is "dead" if every function reading or writing it is in the
unreachable set. This is strictly stronger than "no function accesses
it" because some unreachable functions may reference a global that is
otherwise actually live (used by a different reachable function); the
strict subset is the correct dead-global definition.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Build reachable_accessed = Set of globals read or written by any
   reachable function (walk side_effect_info entries for reachable IDs,
   union memory_reads and memory_writes).
2. For each global in mir.globals: if not in reachable_accessed, append
   to result List.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|reachable_functions| * avg_globals_per_function + |globals|).
Linear in both inputs.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Over-removing live globals would corrupt the binary. The strict-subset
definition above guarantees that any global referenced by a reachable
function survives DCE.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_reachable_filtered_dead_globals" that takes wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let reachable be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    Let side_effect_info be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 64

    If mir is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Build set of accessed-by-reachable globals.
    Let reachable_accessed be proc create from Set
    If side_effect_info is not equal to 0:
        Let func_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with side_effect_info
        Let fi_count be proc length from List with func_ids
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than fi_count:
            Let function_id be proc get from List with func_ids, i
            Let is_reach be proc contains from Set with reachable, function_id
            If is_reach is equal to 1:
                Let ipa be proc get from Dictionary with side_effect_info, function_id
                If ipa is not equal to 0:
                    Let reads be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa, 24
                    If reads is not equal to 0:
                        Let reads_list be proc to_list from Set with reads
                        Let rc be proc length from List with reads_list
                        Let r be 0
                        While r is less than rc:
                            Let r_gid be proc get from List with reads_list, r
                            proc add from Set with reachable_accessed, r_gid
                            Set r to r plus 1
                        End While
                    End If
                    Let writes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ipa, 32
                    If writes is not equal to 0:
                        Let writes_list be proc to_list from Set with writes
                        Let wc be proc length from List with writes_list
                        Let w be 0
                        While w is less than wc:
                            Let w_gid be proc get from List with writes_list, w
                            proc add from Set with reachable_accessed, w_gid
                            Set w to w plus 1
                        End While
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Walk globals; collect those not in reachable_accessed.
    Let globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 16
    Let global_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 24
    If globals is not equal to 0:
        Let g be 0
        While g is less than global_count:
            Let global_var be proc get from List with globals, g
            If global_var is not equal to 0:
                Let global_id be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with global_var, 0
                Let is_accessed be proc contains from Set with reachable_accessed, global_id
                If is_accessed is equal to 0:
                    proc append from List with result, global_id
                End If
            End If
            Set g to g plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc destroy from Set with reachable_accessed
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
compute_dead_types returns the List of type IDs referenced only inside
dead functions. The DCEPlan aggregator uses this as the dead-types
component. Like dead globals, the strict-subset definition is required:
a type referenced by any reachable function survives DCE.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
For the v0.0.8.5 type system, a type is referenced by a function if
the function's parameters, return type, or any local variable type
includes the type ID. The current MIR does not carry an explicit
"types-referenced" set per function, so this helper conservatively
walks the type_hierarchy and for each type checks whether any
reachable function declares it.

The conservative pass walks every reachable function's parameter and
return type metadata in the MIR. The dead_types list contains every
type ID that is in the type_hierarchy but not referenced by any
reachable function.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|types| * |reachable_functions|). For typical programs (a few
hundred types, a few thousand reachable functions), the pass
completes in a few milliseconds.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Over-removing types would break type-hierarchy invariants in the
remaining MIR. The conservative live-types set guarantees that any
type referenced by any reachable function survives.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_dead_types" that takes wpa as Integer, dead_funcs as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let type_hierarchy be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 40
    Let reachable be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0

    If type_hierarchy is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Build set of types referenced by reachable functions.
    Let live_types be proc create from Set

    If mir is not equal to 0:
        Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
        Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8
        If functions is not equal to 0:
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than function_count:
                Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
                If mir_func is not equal to 0:
                    Let fid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0
                    Let is_reach be proc contains from Set with reachable, fid
                    If is_reach is equal to 1:
                        Note: Parameter types at offset 24 (List of type IDs).
                        Let param_types be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 24
                        If param_types is not equal to 0:
                            Let pc be proc length from List with param_types
                            Let p be 0
                            While p is less than pc:
                                Let ptype be proc get from List with param_types, p
                                If ptype is not equal to 0:
                                    proc add from Set with live_types, ptype
                                End If
                                Set p to p plus 1
                            End While
                        End If
                        Note: Return type at offset 32.
                        Let ret_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 32
                        If ret_type is not equal to 0:
                            proc add from Set with live_types, ret_type
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Walk type_hierarchy keys; any type not in live_types is dead.
    Let type_ids be proc keys from Dictionary with type_hierarchy
    Let tc be proc length from List with type_ids
    Let t be 0
    While t is less than tc:
        Let type_id be proc get from List with type_ids, t
        Let is_live be proc contains from Set with live_types, type_id
        If is_live is equal to 0:
            proc append from List with result, type_id
        End If
        Set t to t plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from Set with live_types
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
count_dead_function_bytes estimates the byte savings from deleting
the function with the given ID. Used by score_dce to compute the
size_reduction_bonus for bucket 0x0004 (dead function) priorities.

The estimate is (MIR instruction count) * MIR_BYTES_PER_INST_EST.
This is a heuristic — actual post-codegen byte counts vary — but it
ranks dead functions consistently within a build.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walks mir.functions, finds the function with matching function_id,
sums the instruction counts of its basic blocks, multiplies by the
calibration constant MIR_BYTES_PER_INST_EST.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|MIR|) per call (linear search). Called once per dead function
during score_dce. For a 10k-function program with a few hundred dead
functions, the total cost is ~10M instruction reads, completing in
single-digit milliseconds.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a wrong byte count affects only ranking, not correctness.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "count_dead_function_bytes" that takes function_id as Integer, mir as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8

    If functions is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let inst_total be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        If mir_func is not equal to 0:
            Let fid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0
            If fid is equal to function_id:
                Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
                If cfg is not equal to 0:
                    Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
                    Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24
                    If blocks is not equal to 0:
                        Let b be 0
                        While b is less than block_count:
                            Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                            If block is not equal to 0:
                                Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
                                Set inst_total to inst_total plus inst_count
                            End If
                            Set b to b plus 1
                        End While
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return inst_total multiplied by MIR_BYTES_PER_INST_EST
End Process

@Reasoning
score_inlining computes a priority score for an inlining candidate.
Higher score = higher priority. The formula follows the 10:1:5
cycle:size:enabling weight ratio from the design.

Inputs (inlining candidate offsets):
  offset 0:  caller_id
  offset 8:  callee_id
  offset 16: benefit (already computed by compute_inlining_benefit)
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
The candidate already carries a precomputed benefit value at offset
16 (from compute_inlining_benefit). The score multiplies by
CYCLE_WEIGHT and adds an enabling bonus. Inlining candidates are
already pre-filtered by compute_inlining_benefit to those with
positive expected benefit.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) per call. Inlining-bucket scoring is the cheapest of the eight.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Mis-scoring degrades ranking; no correctness impact.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "score_inlining" that takes candidate as Integer, wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If candidate is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let benefit be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 16
    Let raw be benefit multiplied by CYCLE_WEIGHT
    Let score be raw plus ENABLING_WEIGHT

    If score is less than 0:
        Set score to 0
    End If
    Return score
End Process

@Reasoning
score_devirt computes a priority score for a devirtualization candidate.
Exact devirtualization (confidence=1) eliminates the full indirect
dispatch cost (INDIRECT_CALL_OVERHEAD cycles) plus enables downstream
inlining; speculative devirtualization (confidence=0) saves less
because of the runtime guard overhead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
estimated_cycles_saved depends on confidence:
  confidence=1: full INDIRECT_CALL_OVERHEAD per call site
  confidence=0: INDIRECT_CALL_OVERHEAD - (guard cost ~3 cycles)
enabling_score is ENABLING_WEIGHT * 2 (devirt enables both inlining
and constant propagation).
size_delta is small (one CALL_INDIRECT instruction -> one CALL).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) per call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Score-only function; no correctness impact.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "score_devirt" that takes candidate as Integer, wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If candidate is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let confidence be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with candidate, 16

    Let cycles_saved be INDIRECT_CALL_OVERHEAD
    If confidence is equal to 0:
        Note: Speculative devirt eats ~3 cycles for the runtime guard.
        Set cycles_saved to INDIRECT_CALL_OVERHEAD minus 3
    End If

    Let raw be cycles_saved multiplied by CYCLE_WEIGHT
    Let enabling_score be ENABLING_WEIGHT multiplied by 2
    Let score be raw plus enabling_score
    Note: size_delta for devirt is ~0 (1 instruction replaces 1).
    Return score
End Process

@Reasoning
score_dce computes a priority score for a DCE candidate. The score
incorporates a size_reduction_bonus that is unique to the DCE buckets;
the larger the dead artifact, the higher the priority of deleting it
(removing a 10k-byte dead function is more valuable than removing a
single dead global).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the dce_plan and the candidate index. For bucket 0x0004
(dead function) the size bonus is count_dead_function_bytes; for
buckets 0x0005 (dead global) and 0x0006 (dead type) the size bonus
is a flat 8 bytes (typical global symbol/type record size). The
cycles_saved component is zero (DCE doesn't save cycles, it saves
bytes); the score is dominated by the size bonus.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) for global and type buckets. O(|MIR|) for function bucket (due
to count_dead_function_bytes); called once per dead function.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Mis-scoring degrades ranking only.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "score_dce" that takes dce_plan as Integer, bucket as Integer, index as Integer, wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If dce_plan is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let size_bonus be 0
    If bucket is equal to BUCKET_TAG_DCE_FUNC:
        Let dead_funcs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dce_plan, 0
        If dead_funcs is not equal to 0:
            Let function_id be proc get from List with dead_funcs, index
            Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
            Set size_bonus to count_dead_function_bytes(function_id, mir)
        End If
    End If
    If bucket is equal to BUCKET_TAG_DCE_GLOBAL:
        Set size_bonus to 8
    End If
    If bucket is equal to BUCKET_TAG_DCE_TYPE:
        Set size_bonus to 8
    End If

    Note: DCE saves no cycles directly, only bytes. The CYCLE_WEIGHT
    Note: contribution is zero; ENABLING_WEIGHT applies because
    Note: removing dead code shrinks the working set.
    Let score be (size_bonus multiplied by SIZE_PENALTY_WEIGHT) plus ENABLING_WEIGHT
    Return score
End Process

@Reasoning
score_constant_prop computes a priority score for a CP candidate.
The use_count field of the CPCandidate drives the cycles_saved
component (one LOAD eliminated per use); the value_size_est field
drives the size impact.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walks wpa.constant_prop_candidates to find the candidate whose
global_id matches the input, then reads use_count and value_size_est
from the candidate struct. Score = use_count * CYCLE_WEIGHT + small
enabling bonus.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|CP candidates|) per call (linear search). Called once per
candidate in compute_optimization_priorities; total cost is
O(|CP|²) but |CP| is typically small (a few dozen).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Mis-scoring degrades ranking only.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "score_constant_prop" that takes global_id as Integer, wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cp_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 152
    If cp_candidates is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc length from List with cp_candidates
    Let use_count be 0
    Let value_size_est be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let cand be proc get from List with cp_candidates, i
        If cand is not equal to 0:
            Let gid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cand, 0
            If gid is equal to global_id:
                Set use_count to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cand, 8
                Set value_size_est to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cand, 16
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let cycles_saved be use_count
    Let raw be cycles_saved multiplied by CYCLE_WEIGHT
    Let enabling_score be ENABLING_WEIGHT multiplied by 2
    Let score be raw plus enabling_score

    Note: A high value_size_est means the constant is large; inlining it
    Note: incurs a small size penalty per use site.
    Let size_penalty be value_size_est multiplied by SIZE_PENALTY_WEIGHT
    Set score to score minus size_penalty
    If score is less than 0:
        Set score to 0
    End If
    Return score
End Process

@Reasoning
score_specialization computes a priority score for a specialization
candidate. The benefit field of the SpecCandidate drives the cycles_saved
component (multiplied by caller_count, since each specialization
saves at every call site); a function-size penalty represents the
cost of cloning the function body per specialization.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walks wpa.specialization_candidates to find the candidate whose
function_id matches the input. Reads caller_count and benefit from
the candidate struct. Score formula:

  cycles_saved = benefit * caller_count
  size_penalty = function_size (estimated via count_dead_function_bytes)
  enabling_score = ENABLING_WEIGHT * 4 (specialization unlocks
                   constant folding, inlining, and DCE)
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|spec candidates|) per call. Function-size estimation adds one
MIR walk per scored candidate. Total cost is bounded; |spec
candidates| is typically a few dozen.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Mis-scoring degrades ranking only.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "score_specialization" that takes function_id as Integer, wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let spec_candidates be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 160
    If spec_candidates is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count be proc length from List with spec_candidates
    Let caller_count be 0
    Let benefit be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let cand be proc get from List with spec_candidates, i
        If cand is not equal to 0:
            Let fid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cand, 0
            If fid is equal to function_id:
                Set caller_count to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cand, 8
                Set benefit to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cand, 16
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let cycles_saved be benefit multiplied by caller_count
    Let raw be cycles_saved multiplied by CYCLE_WEIGHT

    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let function_size be count_dead_function_bytes(function_id, mir)
    Let size_penalty be function_size multiplied by SIZE_PENALTY_WEIGHT

    Let enabling_score be ENABLING_WEIGHT multiplied by 4
    Let score be raw plus enabling_score
    Set score to score minus size_penalty
    If score is less than 0:
        Set score to 0
    End If
    Return score
End Process

@Reasoning
allocate_cp_candidate allocates and initializes a CPCandidate struct
(24 bytes) for a constant-global propagation opportunity. The
use_count field reflects how many LOAD instructions across reachable
functions reference this global; value_size_est is the estimated
post-codegen byte cost of the constant value being inlined.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate CP_CANDIDATE_SIZE bytes via Layout.allocate.
2. Walk MIR to count LOAD instructions whose target is this global_id;
   the count populates the use_count field.
3. Estimate value size (MIR_BYTES_PER_INST_EST as a conservative
   default; the actual constant size depends on the type).
4. Return the populated struct pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|MIR|) per call (use-count walk). Called once per constant global
during identify_constant_propagation; total cost is bounded by the
number of distinct constant globals, which is typically small.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. Allocation failure returns 0; caller skips.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "allocate_cp_candidate" that takes global_id as Integer, mir as Integer, wpa as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cand be proc allocate from Layout with CP_CANDIDATE_SIZE
    If cand is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cand, 0, global_id

    Note: Count LOAD-from-global accesses across reachable functions.
    Let use_count be 0
    If mir is not equal to 0:
        Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
        Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8
        Let reachable be 0
        If wpa is not equal to 0:
            Set reachable to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 24
        End If
        If functions is not equal to 0:
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than function_count:
                Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
                If mir_func is not equal to 0:
                    Let fid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0
                    Let counts_this_function be 1
                    If reachable is not equal to 0:
                        Let is_reach be proc contains from Set with reachable, fid
                        If is_reach is equal to 0:
                            Set counts_this_function to 0
                        End If
                    End If

                    If counts_this_function is equal to 1:
                        Let cfg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 8
                        If cfg is not equal to 0:
                            Let blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 16
                            Let block_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cfg, 24
                            If blocks is not equal to 0:
                                Let b be 0
                                While b is less than block_count:
                                    Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
                                    If block is not equal to 0:
                                        Let instructions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 16
                                        Let inst_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block, 24
                                        If instructions is not equal to 0:
                                            Let j be 0
                                            While j is less than inst_count:
                                                Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, j
                                                If inst is not equal to 0:
                                                    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 0
                                                    If opcode is equal to MIR_OP_LOAD:
                                                        Let address be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst, 16
                                                        If address is equal to global_id:
                                                            Set use_count to use_count plus 1
                                                        End If
                                                    End If
                                                End If
                                                Set j to j plus 1
                                            End While
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                    Set b to b plus 1
                                End While
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cand, 8, use_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cand, 16, MIR_BYTES_PER_INST_EST
    Return cand
End Process

@Reasoning
allocate_spec_candidate allocates and initializes a SpecCandidate
struct (32 bytes) for a function-specialization opportunity. The
dominant_const_arg field records the parameter index whose actual
argument is most often a constant across call sites (or -1 if no
clear winner).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate SPEC_CANDIDATE_SIZE bytes via Layout.allocate.
2. Write the four fields (function_id, caller_count, benefit,
   dominant_const_arg).
3. Return the populated struct pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1). All inputs are precomputed; this is just allocate + write.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Allocation failure returns 0; caller skips.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "allocate_spec_candidate" that takes function_id as Integer, caller_count as Integer, benefit as Integer, dominant_const_arg as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cand be proc allocate from Layout with SPEC_CANDIDATE_SIZE
    If cand is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cand, 0, function_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cand, 8, caller_count
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cand, 16, benefit
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with cand, 24, dominant_const_arg
    Return cand
End Process

@Reasoning
find_dominant_constant_arg returns the parameter index whose actual
argument across the function's call sites is most often a compile-time
constant, or -1 if no parameter dominates.

A specialization clone is profitable when at least one parameter is
nearly always passed the same constant (or some constant from a small
set) across the callers — that constant can be inlined into the clone,
unlocking secondary constant folding and dead-code elimination inside
the function body. Picking the wrong dominant index produces a
useless clone (correct, but bigger); picking -1 (no clone) is always
safe.

The "dominance" threshold is 75% of the call sites: a parameter index
qualifies as the dominant_const_arg if at least 75% of its arguments
across all call sites are constants. This threshold is the standard
LLVM/GCC FunctionSpecialization heuristic — below it the clone tends
not to pay for itself; above it the clone reliably shrinks the
specialised hot path. If no parameter clears the threshold (or there
are no call sites, or the function has no parameters) the Process
returns -1 and the specialization apply pass falls back to its
"specialize on no specific argument" path.

The query is performed over the WPA call graph (wpa[8]), which
identify_function_specialization has already populated; the cost is
O(callers * params) where both factors are bounded by the function's
fan-in and arity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Defensive guards: wpa or function_id of 0 returns -1.
2. Look up the function's MIR record by scanning the wpa[0] functions
   List for a matching function_id (the function index in MIR is the
   same shape used by compute_specialization_benefit / get_call_argument
   already in this file). Read param_count at offset 40. If the
   function has zero parameters, return -1.
3. Look up the CallGraphNode at call_graph.nodes[function_id] and read
   the callers List at offset 32 of the node. Each entry is a caller
   function_id (not a CallSite — the CallSite records live on the
   caller's outgoing list).
4. For every caller, scan its call_sites (offset 16 of the caller's
   CallGraphNode) and collect the CallSites whose callee_id == our
   function_id. Each matching CallSite's instruction_ptr (offset 0)
   points to the MIR call instruction which carries the argument
   value_ids in its args List at offset 24 (the same offset
   get_call_argument uses).
5. Build a per-parameter tally Dictionary mapping param_index ->
   constant_count. For each matching call site and each parameter
   index, fetch the argument value_id, walk the wpa[0].value_to_inst
   maps (offset 64 of each MIR function) to find the defining
   instruction, and check its opcode at offset 0. Opcodes
   20001 (CONST), 20002 (CONST_INT/literal), and the MIR LOAD-from-
   constant-global pattern (LOAD with addr defined by GLOBAL_ADDRESS
   to a global_id present in wpa.constant_globals) all qualify as
   "constant" sources.
6. Track total_call_sites separately. Walk the tally Dictionary; for
   each (param_index, count) the dominance ratio is count /
   total_call_sites. The first index whose ratio meets or exceeds 75%
   (i.e. 4*count >= 3*total_call_sites, integer-safe) wins.
7. If no parameter clears the threshold, return -1.

The algorithm is single-pass-per-call-site with constant-time per-arg
work; no recursion into helper passes. helper is_constant_arg below
encapsulates the per-arg-value classification (CONST, CONST_INT, or
LOAD-from-constant-global).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(callers * call_sites_per_caller * param_count). For typical
candidate functions (a few dozen callers, each making one or two
calls into the candidate, a handful of parameters) the cost is
sub-millisecond. The tally Dictionary is allocated fresh per
invocation and destroyed before return; no caching across calls.

Hot path optimisation: the inner loop short-circuits when the
caller's call site does not match the target function_id (the most
common case for callers that contain calls to many functions).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. The Process queries already-parsed MIR plus the
WPA call graph; no untrusted input is read. An incorrect dominant
index (false positive) produces a useless specialization clone but
not a miscompilation — apply_specialization in CMO replays the
constant-fold pipeline before committing the clone, so any predicate
mismatch caught there reverts to the generic version. Returning -1
is always safe: it disables specialization for this candidate.

The 75% threshold encodes a defensive bias: false negatives (no
clone when one would have been profitable) are tolerable; false
positives waste code size. The threshold is documented in the
Reasoning block to allow future tuning if the cost model changes.
@End Security_Scope

@Reasoning
is_constant_arg classifies a single MIR value_id as compile-time
constant (1) or not (0). It is the inner-loop predicate used by
find_dominant_constant_arg when tallying constants per parameter
across call sites.

Three sources qualify as "constant":
  - CONST opcode (20001): a function-address literal or similar
    immediate produced directly by the lexer/parser. The defining
    instruction's immediate value sits at offset 16.
  - CONST_INT/literal opcode (20002): integer/literal constants
    produced by the constant-folding pipeline.
  - LOAD opcode (20200) whose address operand is a global_id present
    in wpa.constant_globals: a load from a global that has been
    proven write-free across the whole program is semantically a
    constant access. constant_globals is populated by Phase 8a's
    identify_global_constants ahead of this helper's invocation.

A defining instruction reached with any other opcode is non-constant
(arithmetic, call result, parameter, phi, etc.). When no defining
instruction is found at all (value_id absent from every MIR function's
value_to_inst map) the value is treated as non-constant — conservative
and safe.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Defensive null/zero guards: mir of 0 or value_id of 0 returns 0.
2. Iterate the MIR functions List at mir[0] up to function_count at
   mir[8]. For each function, look up the value_to_inst Dictionary
   at offset 64; if value_id has a defining instruction there:
     a. Read the opcode at offset 0 of the instruction.
     b. Opcode 20001 (CONST) -> return 1.
     c. Opcode 20002 (CONST_INT/literal) -> return 1.
     d. Opcode 20200 (LOAD) -> read the address operand at offset 16.
        If wpa is non-null and constant_globals (wpa[120]) contains
        the address, return 1.
     e. Any other opcode reached after finding the definition -> the
        value is computed at run time; return 0.
3. If no defining instruction was found in any function (the loop
   completes without returning), return 0.

The helper does NOT recurse: a LOAD from a non-constant address that
itself flows from a CONST is not classified as constant. This matches
the conservative semantics CMO's apply_specialization expects when
seeding the constant-fold pipeline inside a clone.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(|functions|) worst case (one pass over the MIR functions List
looking up value_id in each function's value_to_inst Dictionary).
Each lookup is O(1) on the hashing-based Dictionary primitive. For
typical programs (~10k functions) a non-cached query completes in
microseconds; the early return on first definition usually short-
circuits well before the worst case.

There is no result cache: callers (find_dominant_constant_arg) issue
a small number of queries per candidate, so a cache would not pay
for its bookkeeping cost. If the hot caller density rises in the
future, adding a lazily-allocated Dictionary inside WPA at the
helper's first call would be the natural extension.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Compile-time only. No untrusted input.

Correctness invariant: a value classified as constant MUST have a
genuine compile-time-known producer. False positives would let
find_dominant_constant_arg pick a parameter that is NOT actually
constant, which is itself safe (apply_specialization re-validates the
clone before committing), but degrades optimisation quality. False
negatives (missing genuine constants) reduce specialisation benefit
but never miscompile.

The LOAD-from-constant-global path depends on constant_globals being
populated. If this helper is called before Phase 8a runs the
constant_globals Set will be empty and only CONST/CONST_INT
classifications will succeed — graceful degradation, never crash.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "is_constant_arg" that takes mir as Integer, wpa as Integer, value_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Helper for find_dominant_constant_arg. Returns 1 if the value_id is
    Note: defined by a CONST/literal instruction or loaded from a constant
    Note: global. Otherwise returns 0.
    If mir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If value_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8
    If functions is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Scan every MIR function's value_to_inst map (offset 64) for the
    Note: defining instruction of value_id. The same shape is used by
    Note: compute_points_to_for_value above in this file.
    Let f be 0
    While f is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, f
        If mir_func is not equal to 0:
            Let value_to_inst be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 64
            If value_to_inst is not equal to 0:
                Let def_inst be proc get from Dictionary with value_to_inst, value_id
                If def_inst is not equal to 0:
                    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 0

                    Note: MIR CONST (function-address literal) and the integer/
                    Note: literal CONST opcode both qualify as compile-time
                    Note: constants for specialization purposes.
                    If opcode is equal to 20001:
                        Return 1
                    End If
                    If opcode is equal to 20002:
                        Return 1
                    End If

                    Note: LOAD (20200) from a global address whose global_id is
                    Note: in wpa.constant_globals also qualifies. The LOAD's
                    Note: address operand sits at offset 16 of the instruction.
                    If opcode is equal to 20200:
                        Let load_addr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with def_inst, 16
                        If wpa is not equal to 0:
                            If load_addr is not equal to 0:
                                Let constant_globals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 120
                                If constant_globals is not equal to 0:
                                    Let is_const_global be proc contains from Set with constant_globals, load_addr
                                    If is_const_global is equal to 1:
                                        Return 1
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If

                    Note: Found the definition (not constant) — stop searching.
                    Return 0
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set f to f plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "find_dominant_constant_arg" that takes wpa as Integer, function_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If wpa is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If function_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Let mir be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 0
    Let call_graph be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wpa, 8
    If mir is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If call_graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Note: Step 1 — find the callee's MIR function and read its param_count.
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 0
    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir, 8
    If functions is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Let callee_param_count be 0 minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let mir_func be proc get from List with functions, i
        If mir_func is not equal to 0:
            Let fid be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 0
            If fid is equal to function_id:
                Set callee_param_count to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_func, 40
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If callee_param_count is less than 1:
        Note: No MIR record found, or zero parameters — nothing to specialize on.
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Note: Step 2 — look up the callee's CallGraphNode and read its callers list
    Note: (offset 32). The callers List contains caller function_ids; we then
    Note: walk each caller's outgoing call_sites (offset 16 of the caller's
    Note: node) and select the ones whose callee_id == our function_id.
    Let cg_nodes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with call_graph, 0
    If cg_nodes is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Let callee_node be proc get from Dictionary with cg_nodes, function_id
    If callee_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Let callers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_node, 32
    If callers is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Let caller_list_size be proc length from List with callers
    If caller_list_size is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Note: Step 3 — per-parameter constant-count tally. Use a Dictionary keyed
    Note: by parameter index. total_call_sites accumulates the denominator.
    Let tally be proc create from Dictionary
    Let total_call_sites be 0

    Let c be 0
    While c is less than caller_list_size:
        Let caller_id be proc get from List with callers, c

        Note: Look up the caller's outgoing call sites and pick the ones
        Note: pointing at function_id.
        Let caller_node be proc get from Dictionary with cg_nodes, caller_id
        If caller_node is not equal to 0:
            Let caller_call_sites be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with caller_node, 16
            Let caller_site_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with caller_node, 24

            If caller_call_sites is not equal to 0:
                Let s be 0
                While s is less than caller_site_count:
                    Let cs be proc get from List with caller_call_sites, s
                    If cs is not equal to 0:
                        Let cs_callee be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cs, 8
                        If cs_callee is equal to function_id:
                            Note: This call site targets our candidate. Read its
                            Note: instruction pointer (offset 0 of CallSite) and
                            Note: walk arguments at offset 24 of the MIR call inst.
                            Let inst_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with cs, 0
                            If inst_ptr is not equal to 0:
                                Set total_call_sites to total_call_sites plus 1

                                Let args be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with inst_ptr, 24
                                If args is not equal to 0:
                                    Let arg_list_size be proc length from List with args
                                    Let limit be callee_param_count
                                    If arg_list_size is less than limit:
                                        Set limit to arg_list_size
                                    End If

                                    Let p be 0
                                    While p is less than limit:
                                        Let arg_value_id be proc get from List with args, p
                                        Let is_const be is_constant_arg(mir, wpa, arg_value_id)
                                        If is_const is equal to 1:
                                            Let existing be proc get from Dictionary with tally, p
                                            Let new_count be existing plus 1
                                            proc set from Dictionary with tally, p, new_count
                                        End If
                                        Set p to p plus 1
                                    End While
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set s to s plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set c to c plus 1
    End While

    If total_call_sites is equal to 0:
        proc destroy from Dictionary with tally
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If

    Note: Step 4 — find the parameter index whose constant-count meets the 75%
    Note: dominance threshold. 4*count >= 3*total_call_sites is the integer-safe
    Note: form of count/total >= 0.75. Tie-break by lowest parameter index.
    Let best_index be 0 minus 1
    Let best_count be 0
    Let threshold_num be 3 multiplied by total_call_sites

    Let tally_keys be proc keys from Dictionary with tally
    Let tally_size be proc length from List with tally_keys

    Let tk be 0
    While tk is less than tally_size:
        Let pidx be proc get from List with tally_keys, tk
        Let pcount be proc get from Dictionary with tally, pidx
        Let scaled be 4 multiplied by pcount

        If scaled is greater than or equal to threshold_num:
            If pcount is greater than best_count:
                Set best_count to pcount
                Set best_index to pidx
            Otherwise:
                If pcount is equal to best_count:
                    If best_index is less than 0:
                        Set best_index to pidx
                    Otherwise:
                        If pidx is less than best_index:
                            Set best_index to pidx
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set tk to tk plus 1
    End While

    proc destroy from Dictionary with tally

    Return best_index
End Process
